<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Seizes Over 8 Tons of Narcotics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Iran's security forces seized
some 8,874 kilograms of morphine-based drugs in the past two weeks
in the northeastern province of Khorasan, the Islamic Republic News
Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 Afghan drug-dealers were killed and 1,281 other
drug-dealers were arrested in 57 operations in the period,
according to Bahram Nowruzi, an officer of the provincial security
forces.
</P>
<P>
He added that 66 rifles and several rounds of ammunition as well
as 87 cars and 29 motorbikes were confiscated in the operations.
</P>
<P>
Drug hauls have become very common in Iran as it sits on a major
route for smuggling narcotics from the eastern neighbors of
Afghanistan and Pakistan to the lucrative markets in the Persian
Gulf, Europe and Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
In July, Iran closed down 725 kilometers of borders with its
eastern neighbor Afghanistan as part of the stepped-up efforts to
fight drug trade and threats to its security.
</P>
<P>
The parliament has also earmarked 200 billion rials (about 24.4
million U.S. dollars) in credits to block the total 950 kilometers
of eastern borders from drug traffic.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, 740 drug traffickers and 174 Iranian police officers
were killed in narcotics-related confrontations, according to
government reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
