<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000 GMT, September 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon's former prime minister Rafik al-Hariri scored
a landslide victory in Sunday's parliamentary elections, capturing
18 of the 19 seats in capital Beirut.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Star newspaper reported Monday that initial results in
the southern Lebanon and eastern Bekaa valley districts showed the
Resistance and Development list, anchored by Hezbollah and Amal
militias, headed for victory over several incomplete tickets.
(Lebanon-Election)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss Monday conceded
defeat in the parliamentary elections and accused his rival former
Premier Rafik al-Hariri of using political money to influence the
elections.
</P>
<P>
"I accept the result democratically and I will act according to
it," Hoss said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
However, Hoss denied reports on his resignation and confirmed
that he will not withdraw from the political scene and will work
outside the parliament. (Lebanon-PM-Elections)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Communications Minister Binyamin Ben
Eliezer Monday signed a series of regulations to open Israel's
domestic telecommunications market to competition.
</P>
<P>
The statutes, approved in a vote by Israeli Knesset's
(parliament) Finance Committee members early Monday, are aiming to
end the market monopoly by the state-owned Bezeq, or Israeli
Telecom company. (Israel-Telecoms)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Arab foreign ministers ended a two-day meeting here on
Monday with a call for the Middle East peace talks to proceed
according to United Nations Security Council resolutions and the
land-for-peace principle.
</P>
<P>
Final resolutions issued late Sunday night, the 114th session of
the Foreign Ministers Council of the 22-member Arab League,
expressed support for the Palestinians in their final-status
negotiations with Israel and for Syria in its frozen peace talks
with the Jewish state. (Arab League-Council Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- A senior Palestinian official said here on Monday that
the Palestinians may not declare an independent state on September
13 as they have previously planned.
</P>
<P>
September 13 is not "a sacred date," and since the Palestinians
and Israel will continue their negotiations the Palestinians are
unlikely to declare a state that day, said Farouk al Kadoumy,
director of the political department of the Palestine Liberation
Organization (PLO). (Arab League-Palestine-Statehood) 
</P>
</TEXT>
