<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Prepares Poverty Reduction Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa Monday said that his government has prepared a
poverty reduction strategy with emphasis on agriculture and
education.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa, who is traveling across the country on a campaign tour,
said that the strategy, to be presented to the World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) and other donors next week, is
designed to speed up the campaign against poverty within the next
10 years.
</P>
<P>
According to the strategy, Tanzania is aimed at boosting its
economic growth from the present 4.0 percent to between 7 to 10
percent, which can afford reducing the abject poverty facing most
Tanzanians who survive on 0.65 US dollars per day or less.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank, IMF and other donors have asked Tanzania to
prepare the strategy as a condition for finalizing over two
billion US dollars being debt relief to Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said the government gave education and agriculture its
due importance in the allocation of national resources.
</P>
<P>
"We must modernize our farming system and improve education to
enable the people to have skills needed to manage a modern economy,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
With a foreign debt of around 6 billion US dollars, Tanzania
has been spending about 40 per cent of its annual budget to repay
matured debts.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the heavy debt burden and Tanzania's strive for
sound macro-economic stability, the country qualified early this
year as a potential candidate to get massive debt relief under
HIPC.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa urged his people to work hard and use their labor power,
knowledge and skills to produce crops and manufactured goods of
high quality and in large quantities to sell in the domestic
market and abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
