<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Gives States Ultimatum to Stop Pipeline Vandalism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian government has given
some of the country' s states two weeks of ultimatum to put an end
to wide spread oil pipeline vandalism.
</P>
<P>
News Agency of Nigeria Monday quoted the ultimatum as warning
that the federal government might send in troops to help stop the
vandalism if the state governments fail to do so.
</P>
<P>
The warning was given at an emergency meeting Monday in Abuja
attended by vice-president of the country, Inspector-General of
the Police, Boss of the Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation (
NNPC), and governors or deputy governors of the concerned states,
including Edo, Delta, Abia, Rivers, and Bayelsa, and Cross rivers.
</P>
<P>
The States, where NNPC' s pipelines pass through, were ordered
by the federal government to set up independent anti-vandalism
monitoring teams to check the incidence of the menace.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics provided by the meeting, about 400
leakage caused by vandalism have taken place this year, causing
loses worth billions of naira.
</P>
<P>
Pipeline fires caused by vandalism took hundreds of lives in
August this year in the country' s Niger Delta region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
