<HEADLINE> Switzerland Urges India Not to Carry Out New Nuclear Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Switzerland has called on India
not to carry out any more nuclear tests, according to a Swiss
Radio International report.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting Monday in the Swiss capital of Berne,
Swiss Foreign Minister Joseph Deiss told his Indian counterpart
Jaswant Singh that India should show restraint in that aspect.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland is among countries which have condemned the
underground nuclear tests carried out by India and Pakistan in
1998 and urged them to sign the nuclear non-proliferation treaty.
</P>
<P>
Deiss also said that Switzerland is willing to mediate at any
time between India and Pakistan over the Kashmir conflict.
</P>
<P>
However, the Indian foreign minister responded that there is no
need for outside intervention. "The need to mediate and facilitate
does not arise since India and Pakistan speak the same language,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Singh stressed the need for more frequent meetings between the
two countries. His visit to Berne was the first by an Indian
foreign minister for nearly 20 years. The Swiss foreign ministry
said Deiss has received an official invitation from India and may
pay a return visit next year.
</P>
<P>
Singh also discussed ways to strengthen business and trade ties
with Swiss Economics Minister Pascal Couchepin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
