<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania Stages 1st European Conference on Electronic Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The first European
Conference for Electronic Trade opened in Bucharest on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"This conference belongs to a wave of preoccupations by the
Central and Eastern European countries, and its main target is
both the estimation of the commitment level of the education and
research staff in this trade's development, as well as the
improvement of the international relations in the field," the
director of the Electronic Trade Initiative Center, Professor
Gheorghe Sandulescu said at the conference.
</P>
<P>
"The conference will play an important part in the
implementation of the electronic trade, which is to enable the
development of the small and middle-size units and the access to
the under globalization current milieus," Sandulescu stressed.
</P>
<P>
The seminars held by professors and researchers from Romania,
the United States, Italy, the Netherlands, and Britain approached
a wide scaled topics such as the economic and IT aspects, global
electronic trade, insurance system by Internet or trade orders by
mobile phones, as well as social, juridical aspects of the
implementation of such solutions.
</P>
<P>
The researchers belonging to the Center for Electronic Trade of
Texas University showed that the bulk of electronic transactions
on Internet increased from 5 billion U.S. dollars, in 1995 to over
300 billion, in 1998, while during the same span, the U.S. GDP
grew from 6,762 billion to 7,552 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
As many as 562 million Internet users are expected in Europe in
the year 2003, or 465 percent more, under the circumstances when
there were 142 million in the year 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Internet could be the single business way in the year 2005,
experts held. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
