<HEADLINE> Israel Says Middle East Peace Process at "Critical Juncture" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak told U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan Monday that the
Middle East peace process is at a "critical juncture" and must be
resolved in a matter of weeks.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who is here to attend the Millennium Summit to be held
from September 6 to 8, had a 35-minute meeting with the U.N.
secretary-general focusing on the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
"It does not have to be a matter of days. But it can't be a
matter of months. We're talking about several weeks," Barak told
the U.N. chief, according to his spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press on his hopes for peace, Barak said, "I do
hope, I pray. But I don't know."
</P>
<P>
Barak's meeting with the U.N. chief at the Headquarters of the
United Nations in New York kicked off a series of talks the
Israeli prime minister will hold with world leaders during the
Millennium Summit.
</P>
<P>
Among the leaders Barak is scheduled to meet this week are:
British Prime Minister Tony Blair, French President Jacques Chirac
and Russian President Vladimir Putin.  
</P>
</TEXT>
