<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates' National Bank of Ras Al
Khaimah plans to start reporting quarterly interim financial
results from this month, in anticipation of the demand for more
regular and open disclosures from stock exchange regulatory
authorities.
</P>
<P>
The bank was the first in the UAE to release its half-yearly
results, in 1998.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Department of Tourism and Commerce Marketing
(DTCM) in Dubai recently has attracted more than 175 major South
African businessmen, who expressed a keen interest in the Middle
East market and Dubai, following a relaxation of exchange controls
in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The number of South African companies in Dubai and Jebel Ali
Free Zone increased from last year's 23 to 27 this year.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The UAE's Sharjah Chamber of Commerce and Industry
(SCCI) and the Australian Deakin University are jointly planning
technology management programs for executives.
</P>
<P>
The programs are designed to help senior professionals to offer
new ideas to take companies to new heights, in addition to the
normal educational information.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Some 100 Turkish companies will attend the 33rd
Baghdad International Fair scheduled on November 1-10.
</P>
<P>
According to a written statement issued by Forum Fuarcilik
company Monday, Turkish exhibits will include medical,
agricultural, construction and telecommunication equipment,
automotive sub-industry products, plastic, paper and textile
products and other household products.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- "Informatics 2000 Fair" will be held in Istanbul on
September 6-10.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,000 companies, including 50 from 11 foreign countries,
will have stands in the fair, in which thousands of new products
and services will be promoted.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the fair is "New Avenues in the Internet" and its
slogan is "Reaching unlimited horizons."
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Omani Central Bank said on Sunday that it had
decided not to issue this year's third government development bond
planned for September, worth about 78 million dollars, due to an
improved financial situation in the Gulf state.
</P>
<P>
The bank may not issue any more bonds this year because of
higher world oil prices, a bank official said.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Philippines is to establish a joint consultative
committee with the UAE.
</P>
<P>
Lauro Baja, undersecretary of Philippine Foreign Ministry, said
that the proposal to set up the committee has already been handed
to his ministry.
</P>
<P>
Philippines has recently signed similar agreements with Iran,
Kuwait and Egypt to boost bilateral economic, political and socio-
cultural ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
