<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab FMs Approve Draft Appendix to Arab League Concerning Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Arab foreign ministers have
approved a draft appendix to the Arab League (AL) charter that
would provide for a summit meeting to be held in March each year,
AL Secretary General Esmat Abdel-Meguid said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The ministers gave the approval during the two-day 114th session
of the league's Foreign Ministers Council, Abdel-Meguid told a news
conference at the end of the meetings.
</P>
<P>
A committee grouping the foreign ministers of Egypt, Oman,
Tunisia, Syria and Yemen and the AL chief submitted a proposal to
the council meetings on holding annual Arab summits to discuss all
key issues related to the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
Until now, the league's charter has made no provisions for
summits and considers the ministerial council as the league's
highest body.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid said the foreign ministers would convene an
extraordinary meeting in October to consider arrangements
concerning the proposed appendix and to prepare for the summit next
year.
</P>
<P>
Following that meeting, the matter would go to member states for
their ratification, after which the appendix would become part of
the charter and enter into force, he added.
</P>
<P>
This would be the first appendix to the Arab League charter,
which came into effect in 1945 when the league was founded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PLO Official Rules out Statehood Declaration on September 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 4 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian official
said here on Monday that the Palestinians may not declare an
independent state on September 13 as they have previously planned.
</P>
<P>
September 13 is not "a sacred date," and since the Palestinians
and Israel will continue their negotiations the Palestinians are
unlikely to declare a state that day, said Farouk al Kadoumy,
director of the political department of the Palestine Liberation
Organization (PLO).
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat is going to New York to meet
with United States President Bill Clinton and discuss with him ways
of seeking breakthroughs in the Palestinian-Israeli peace
negotiations, Kadoumy told a news conference after the 114th
session of the Arab League Foreign Ministers Council held in the
Egyptian capital.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Clinton are due to meet on the sidelines of the
United Nations Millennium Summit on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The PLO's 129-member central council are reportedly to meet in
Gaza on September 9 and 10 to review the Palestinians' commitment
to declare statehood on September 13. Palestinian officials have
already suggested the move could be deferred.
</P>
<P>
Kadoumy also said it is not Arafat's job, but a job of an Arab
summit to declare an end to the conflict with Israel. Arafat can
not proclaim an end to the conflict because it is a decision that
should be taken by an Arab summit, he said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has said several times that a
final peace accord with the Palestinians must include a statement
declaring an end to their conflict which has lasted over half a
century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Decisions to be Made After Assessments of Talks: Cyprus FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Greek Cypriot side will
participate in the fourth round of U.N.-sponsored proximity talks
and any decisions will be made on the basis of the assessments of
the talks, Cyprus Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides made the remark on his departure for New York to join
Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides, who arrived there Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on statements recently made by Greek Prime Minister
Costas Simitis that it would be wrong for the Greek Cypriot side to
leave the negotiating table, Kasoulides said "his approach is not
different to ours. We are participating in this dialogue
constructively."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at Larnaca airport, southern coast of the island,
Kasoulides made it clear that "we will assess our stance at the end
of this negotiating process and in the light of the facts we will
have before us, in coordination with the Greek government, and the
decision that will be taken by the National Council."
</P>
<P>
The members of the National Council, top advisory body to the
president on the Cyprus issue comprising the leaders of the five
parliamentary parties, will be in New York when the talks resume,
to be available for consultation with President Clerides.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern third of the Mediterranean island after a failed coup in
Nicosia seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Three rounds of proximity talks, or indirect talks between the
two sides through U.N. staffs shuttling between them, have been
held so far, which were aimed at paving the way for substantive
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The fourth round of talks is due to start in New York on
September 12.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Michalis Papapetrou said that if no
substantive consultations take place in New York and if there are
no developments, the assessment is that this round of talks will
end before October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian Officials Visit Iraq for Closer Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Visiting senior Jordanian
officials said here Monday that their visit to Iraq was aimed at
enhancing bilateral relations in all fields, not just in the
economic field.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Minister of Trade and Industry Wasif Azar and Minister
of Transport Mohammad Kalaldeh arrived here on Monday evening for a
four-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival, Azar expressed the hope that the visit could serve
to boost overall cooperation between Jordan and Iraq, the official
Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
"This visit is complementary to the previous visits made by
other Jordanian government ministers," Kalaldeh said, adding that
they will discuss how to promote bilateral trade exchanges through
land and sea transportation.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Trade Minister Mohammad Mehdi Salah, who welcomed his
Jordanian counterparts, said Jordan is among Iraq's most important
trade partners in the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
According to Jordan's official statistics, Iraq exported to
Jordan various products valued at some 206 million U.S. dollars in
the first half of this year, which accounted for 67 percent of
Jordan's total imports.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, the only source of crude for Jordan, provides the kingdom
with 50,000 to 750,000 barrels of oil per day at a preferential
price of 19 dollars per barrel, which is much lower than the
international market prices.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two Arab neighbors have witnessed a major
improvement following the July visit to Amman by Iraqi Vice
President Taha Yassin Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein held talks with the Iraqi
vice president. It was the first time for the Jordanian king to
meet a senior Iraqi official since he assumed the throne in
February last year.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Prime Minister Ali Abu Ragheb, who took office on June
19, has pledged closer ties with Iraq and to help end the United
Nations sanctions imposed on Baghdad after its invasion of Kuwait
in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
