<HEADLINE> Tanzania Urges Investment in Regional Trade Corridor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania on Monday urged
the four countries involved in the planned Mtwara Development
Corridor to attract investment in the project.
</P>
<P>
Opening a three-day workshop on the corridor here on Monday,
Permanent Secretary in the Ministry of Works, Solomon Odunga, said
the project has enormous potential for creating jobs and bringing
about rapid economic growth in the region, which includes Tanzania,
Malawi, Mozambique and Zambia.
</P>
<P>
"Member countries of the corridor should improve the investment
climate in the region with a view to linking them with other
countries, other development corridors and the global economy," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The corridor project is to build a 820-kilometer highway from
the Mtwara Port on Tanzania's southeast coast to Lake Nyasa as a
shortcut for the transportation of goods from the Indian Ocean to
landlocked Malawi and Zambia. It is also expected to spur economic
development in northern Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
However, shortage of funds has hampered the implementation of
the project. Bureaucracy, poor infrastructure are also cited as
snag to investors in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
