<HEADLINE> Georgia Faces Famine Due to Record Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Georgian Agriculture and Food
Minister David Kirvalidze said Monday that a record drought this
summer might plunge his country into famine.
</P>
<P>
The drought, which destroyed almost all grain crops and many of
the vineyards, cost Georgia some 200 million U.S. dollars in
economic loss, the Interfax news agency quoted Kirvalidze as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The minister said a Red Cross report about the threat of famine
in Georgia related to drought "is quite true."
</P>
<P>
He said Georgian President Eduard Shevardnadze had appealed to
international organizations and countries for aid in overcoming
the consequences of the drought. He said there is hope that the
European Union, the United States and some neighboring countries
will grant Tbilisi seeds and diesel fuel for autumn-time sowing.
</P>
<P>
Independent experts say Georgia will not be able to overcome
the aftermath of the drought alone, because it does not have
enough hard currency to import food, Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
Many of the country's poor population will face a difficult
winter ahead, the experts predicted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
