<HEADLINE> Somalia's New President to Attend Millennium Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Somalia's new president
will attend the Millennium Summit to be held from September 6 to 8
at the United Nations headquarters in New York, African diplomats
said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Abdiqassim Salad Hassan, who was elected a week ago by a
parliament operating out of the neighboring state of Djibouti,
will arrive in New York late Monday from Cairo where he addressed
a meeting of Arab foreign ministers, the African diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
The diplomats said Salad had the blessing of the Organization
of African Unity, the Arab League and some European countries.
</P>
<P>
His representation at the Millennium Summit will end more than
a decade's isolation of his impoverished nation, the diplomats
added.
</P>
<P>
Somalia has been without a central government since 1991. Clan
leaders from across Somalia gathered in Djibouti in May of this
year to work out a plan to restore some sort of order to the
fractured nation.
</P>
<P>
A 245-member parliament was created three weeks ago with
representatives from all of Somalia's clans and sub-clans.
Elections were promised after a three-year transitional period.
</P>
<P>
With Salad's representation, only two of the 188 U.N. member
states will not send their highest-ranking representatives to the
summit, namely Kiribati and Yugoslavia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
