<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Acting FM Discusses Peace Process With Moroccan King </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Acting Foreign
Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami visited Morocco on Monday to discuss the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process with King Mohammed VI there,
officials in Israeli Foreign Ministry confirmed.
</P>
<P>
A short statement issued by the ministry said that Ben-Ami, who
was born in Morocco and later immigrated to Israel, met King
Mohammed VI for about two hours.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, officials said that Ben-Ami left Israel for secret
negotiations abroad, but declined to reveal his destination and
other details.
</P>
<P>
The two, the statement said, discussed the current situation of
the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, which had hit a deadlock since
the Camp David summit in July failed to reach any agreement due to
significant gaps between the two sides over the fate of Jerusalem
and the return of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Ben-Ami reportedly relay the message to King
Mohammed VI that now is the "moment of truth" for Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat to make a brave decision. Otherwise, the
statement added, the talks will be endless.
</P>
<P>
In the past few weeks, Israel had repeatedly urged Arafat to
show more openness and flexibility in the talks. However, the
Palestinians insisted that Israel should be the side that makes
further compromises in future talks.
</P>
<P>
As chairman of the Jerusalem Committee of the Organization of
the Islamic Conference, the Moroccan monarch convened a committee
meeting last week to show Arab countries' support to Arafat's
stands on the Jerusalem issue.
</P>
<P>
It was believed that the Moroccan monarch and the Israeli
minister discussed the thorniest issue in Monday's meeting, which
had become the bottleneck of the peace track.
</P>
<P>
Israel claimed the holy city as its "eternal and undivided
capital," while the Palestinians want at least East Jerusalem,
which Israel occupied in the 1967 Mideast war, to be the capital of
their future state.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also discussed the development of bilateral
relations between Israel and Morocco, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Ben-Ami, who also holds the Public Security portfolio, took over
the foreign ministry after his predecessor David Levy resigned in
the wake of Camp David peace summit.
</P>
<P>
Ben-Ami had played an active role in the talks since May when he
and Palestinian Legislative Council Speaker Ahmed Qurei (Abu Ala)
launched the so-called "back-channel" negotiations in Stockholm. He
also participated in the Camp David talks.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak is now also abroad as he has
arrived in New York for the United Nations' Millennium Summit
there. He is scheduled to hold meetings with United States
President Bill Clinton, who will later meet with Arafat separately.
</P>
<P>
The meetings, the first since the Camp David talks, are widely
regarded as the last chance for reviving the Israeli-Palestinian
talks in the next few weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
