<HEADLINE> NATO to Conduct Maneuvers in Kazakhstan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) and its Partnership for Peace countries will
conduct joint maneuvers Kazakhstan on September 10-20, Turkey's
Anatolia News Agency reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Land Forces Commandership said in a statement on
Monday that the maneuvers, code-named "Centrasbat-2000", will be
aimed at improving the technical and tactical principles in the
humanitarian rescue operations.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Turkey, Britain, Russia, Azerbaijan, Georgia,
Kyrgyzstan, Mongolia, Uzbekistan, Ukraine and Kazakhstan, will take
part in the military exercises, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
During the 10-day drill, Turkey and the United States will
launch an air maneuver on September 10-11.
</P>
<P>
Following the preparation phase on September 14-15, said the
statement, full-scaled maneuvers will be launched on September 16-
17.
</P>
<P>
Turkey will despatch a total of 34 personnel from the Land
Forces to take part in the maneuver, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The 19-member NATO, a Western political and military bloc which
was founded on April 4, 1949 in the Cold War ear, was not disbanded
at the end of the Cold War, but extended eastward last year.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, NATO also initiated a "Partnership for Peace " program,

which was joined by more than 20 European countries and former
Soviet republics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
