<HEADLINE> Iraq to Hold International Tourism Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 4 (Xinhua)-- Iraq has invited 150 tourism
experts from countries worldwide to take part in the upcoming
International Tourism Week in the country, local media reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview, Raheem Karim, director general of the Iraqi
Tourism Committee subordinate to the Ministry of Culture and
Information, said the International Tourism Week has been part of
Iraq's efforts to rejuvenate the country's tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
The Tourism Committee will bring the international experts to
Iraq's scenic spots and ask their opinion about how to develop
Iraq's
tourism, Karim said.
</P>
<P>
If the international experts can draw up good tourism
development
plans, the Tourism Committee is ready to buy them over at a high
price, he added.
</P>
<P>
The 150 tourism experts who have been invited by Iraq are from
Indonesia, Lebanon, Bahrain, Japan, Jordan, Syria, Egypt, Kenya,
France, Germany, Switzerland and other Asian, African and European
countries.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, with an ancient civilization of over 6,000 years, used to
be a tourism powerhouse with numerous world-famous cultural and
historic sites.
</P>
<P>
But Iraq's tourism industry has suffered heavily since the
United Nations imposed sweeping economic sanctions following Iraq's
invasion of Kuwait in August 1990. 
</P>
