<HEADLINE> SADC Peacekeeping Cooperation Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Deputy commander of the
Botswana Defense Force Tebogo Masire called Monday for more joint
training exercises and coordination in peacekeeping operations in
the southern African region.
</P>
<P>
He told a conference in Johannesburg that there was virtually
no combined peacekeeping training in the Southern African
Development Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
"I am sure you will agree that the recent relief operations in
Mozambique did not reflect the combined operations that we dream
of," he said.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 SADC mission to restore stability in Lesotho after an
army mutiny also exposed common shortcomings such as inadequate
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
"A lot is still to be done to achieve an above average grade in
combined operations," Masire said.
</P>
<P>
He said a first step to improve coordination would be to set up
some kind of peacekeeping office within the secretariat of SADC.
In this way, the momentum of motivation for SADC members to train
together would be maintained, he added.
</P>
<P>
Masire said an inventory should also be compiled of precisely
what each SADC member could contribute to peacekeeping missions.
</P>
</TEXT>
