<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poor Economic Situation Blamed For Child Labor in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization (
WHO) says the poor economic situation in African countries has led
to unemployment, low income and high levels of poverty.
</P>
<P>
This has resulted in high levels of child labor and a huge
problem of street children.
</P>
<P>
World Health Organization country representative Edward Maganu
said child survival and welfare is a challenge, adding that there
is need to address priorities for improving the welfare of
children.
</P>
<P>
Maganu was speaking when he officiated at the Christian
Children's Fund(CCF) workshop on the integration of psycho-social
aspects in programming in Lusaka on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said HIV/AIDS pandemic is another serious threat to the
survival and welfare of children because it has left them as
orphans through the death of parents or guardians.
</P>
<P>
Maganu noted that the support that CCF is providing to Zambia
is broad based and multisectoral, adding that it is a clear
demonstration that the organization is committed to supplementing
government efforts in development.
</P>
<P>
He added that poverty should be alleviated at all levels
because it compromises the ability of families to provide their
children's needs.
</P>
<P>
"Sustainable development at community level requires that
families should have the means to raise healthy children and give
them good education. We should remember that children are the
future of our nations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Maganu however commended the Zambian government for creating an
enabling environment for the implementation of child survival and
welfare programs as demonstrated through the declaration of 1992
as "The Year of the Zambian Child".
</P>
<P>
Speaking earlier CCF Zambia national director Joe Konte said
the workshop would improve the participants knowledge and skills
in planning, programming and implementation of appropriate
strategies.
</P>
<P>
Konte urged the participants to utilize the deliberations fully
in order to find effective means of empowering the communities
they serve.
</P>
</TEXT>
