<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Tourist Killed by Wild Elephant in Namibia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 JOHANNESBURG, September 4 (Xinhua) -- A wild elephant
killed one American tourist and injured another during a wildlife
tour in remote northwestern Namibia, the South African Press
Association reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the American tourist named Dean Hall
was killed instantly and Dr. A. Said was injured when a desert
elephant charged a group of tourists trying to photograph it in
the Huab River Valley.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary reports indicated the tourists had left their
vehicle and walked between two groups of elephants from the same
herd, said Ben Beytel, a senior official with the Ministry of
Environment and Tourism.
</P>
<P>
By moving between the two herds, the tourists would appear to
be a threat to the desert elephants, a unique subspecies that has
adapted to the arid conditions of the Namibian desert, he said.
</P>
<P>
"They seemed to have been as close as 30 meters from the
smaller group before they realized the danger," he said. "There
are some calves with that group, and there also appears to be a
rather aggressive cow with the same herd," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hall died within minutes of the attack and Said suffered a
broken arm and a knee injury, a medical air-rescue worker told The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
"The whole situation played itself out in a matter of 10 to 15
seconds," Said was quoted as saying by the report.
</P>
<P>
Hall's death was the third in the 25,000 sq.-kilometer- area
in three years, Beytel said.
</P>
<P>
"The problem is the tourists forget that the animals are wild,
and that they are often spooked by people coming too close to them,
" he said. "We do not see the elephant cow as a problem animal yet.
" 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
