<HEADLINE> Child Abuse on the Increase in South Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Child abuse was on the
rise at an unprecedented rate in South Africa with more than 40,
000 cases recorded by police in the past year alone, Jacqueline
Loffell of the Johannesburg Child Welfare Society said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing delegates at a three-day international conference on
child abuse and neglect in Johannesburg, Loffell said two children
were raped every hour. This was the tip of the iceberg because
statistics did not include the rape of boys, she added.
</P>
<P>
There were also more than 3,000 children abandoned each year,
resulting in increased child exploitation for commercial sex, she
said.
</P>
<P>
Loffell said the 17 million children in the country made up 40
percent of the population and South Africa was facing major
challenges in establishing protection mechanisms for children.
</P>
<P>
"We need an efficient child protection system because the one
we currently have is very patchy," she said.
</P>
<P>
Professor Noel Zaal, a member of the South Africa Law
Commission, said South Africa had to urgently look at legislation
to protect the rights of children.
</P>
<P>
Zaal called for a broader welfare grant system because the
current one was not easily accessible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
