<HEADLINE> Estrada Leaves to Attend U.N. Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada left here Monday night for New York to attend the United
Nations Millennium Summit starting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
As part of his diplomatic and trade mission, Estrada will also
make a working visit to San Francisco, Chicago and Honolulu during
his U.S. trip, the Presidential Palace said earlier in a press
release.
</P>
<P>
Some 150 heads of state and government from all over the world
have confirmed their attendance in the summit which the United
Nations has described as "the largest ever gathering of world
leaders."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. summit, which will coincide with the opening of the
55th session of the U.N. General Assembly, will be held from
September 6 to 8.
</P>
<P>
Press Undersecretary Michael Toledo, who is a member of the
Philippine delegation, said earlier that President Estrada would
be the 26th speaker in the U.N. summit to be held at the U.N.
General Assembly Hall.
</P>
<P>
Before delivering his address, the president will sign, on
behalf of the Philippine government, two U.N. multilateral accords
namely the "Convention on the Rights of the Child, Optional
Protocol on the Involvement of Children in Armed Conflicts" and
the "Convention of the Rights of the Child, Optional Protocol on
the Sale of Children, Child Prostitution and Child Pornography,"
according to Toledo.
</P>
<P>
As part of his diplomatic thrust, while at the U.N.
headquarters, the president will also hold bilateral meetings with
his counterparts from Indonesia, Qatar, Morocco, Saudi Arabia,
Senegal, Iran and Bangladesh, Toledo said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
