<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Intensifies Development of Telecommunications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam is striving to raise the
number of telephone subscribers to 3 million by the end of this
month, Vietnam News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam had 2.95 million telephone subscribers by the end of
August or approximately four telephones per 100 people, according
to the Vietnam Post and Telecommunications Corporation (VNPT).
</P>
<P>
Vietnam plans to gain a year-on-year increase of 80 percent in
telephone expansion as it installs 18,000-20,000 telephones per
week.
</P>
<P>
VNPT is preparing to link its mobile network with international
ones. Agreement has been reached with 80 foreign partners for
provision of mobile phone services and with 25 others for
exploiting its two mobile phone networks, Vinaphone and Mobiphone.
</P>
<P>
The country's international network was officially linked to
the international undersea fibber optic cable named SEA-ME-WE3
along with 34 European, Asian and American countries in 1998.
</P>
<P>
There are now 5,764 direct international channels, with 60
percent operating through fibber optic cables and the remainder
through satellite, thus enabling thousands of international calls
to be carried out simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
In its strategy until 2020, Vietnam plans to raise the number
of telephones for every 100 people to 12-15 by 2010 and 20-25 by
2020, and the rate of households using telephones to 50 percent
and 75 percent in 2010 and 2020, respectively. Its turnover will
be 3 billion U.S. dollars in 2010.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam ranked second in the world in terms of telephone
subscription growth in 1999, becoming one of 30 countries
worldwide with more than 2 million phone lines, according to the
International Telecommunications Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
