<HEADLINE> British Hostages in S. Leone to Be Freed Soon: Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The British military mission in
Sierra Leone has expressed optimism that all six soldiers still
being held hostage by the rebel West Side Boys would soon be freed.
</P>
<P>
Talks with the rebel group are progressing well, a spokesman
for the mission was quoted as saying by reports reaching here on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The West Side Boys captured 11 British soldiers on August 25.
Those soldiers were among the hundreds staying in Sierra Leone to
help training the country's national army in the densely-forested
Occra Hills area, about 80 kilometers from the capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
Relatives of the West Side Boys are expected to leave Freetown
on Monday for the rebel group's base to make a fresh appeal for
the release of the captives, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The first such plea was made last Tuesday, the day before five
of the captives were released.
</P>
<P>
The West Side Boys had demanded the release of their supporters
from jail, a review of Sierra Leone's peace agreement and their
integration into the country's army, all of which were refused by
the government.
</P>
<P>
The Sierra Leonean government has reiterated several times its
determination not to make concessions to the hostage-takers.
</P>
