<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prodi Supports Debate on Therapeutical Cloning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Romano Prodi, president of
the commission of the European Union (EU) on Monday expressed his
support for the debate on the therapeutical cloning.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that the commission should assist a public debate
that resembles the common values of the European Community," said
Prodi in a written statement issued by the commission.
</P>
<P>
He expected that an equilibrium could be struck through the
debate between the ethical concerns and the commercial aspects of
the therapeutical cloning.
</P>
<P>
The EU, however, is opposed to cloning of human embryos. The
union's fifth Framework Program for Research and Technology
Development from 1998 to 2002 excludes financial support for any
research projects concerning the cloning of human embryos for the
purpose of reproduction.
</P>
<P>
Therapeutical cloning involves two basic techniques -- cellular
therapy and formation of embryos via cloning.
</P>
<P>
Cellular therapy, already used for several years already to
cure such diseases as leukemia, aims at replacing diseased human
cells or increasing insufficient cells in human bodies.
</P>
<P>
While it has a prospect of being able to cure degenerative
diseases including the Alzheimer and Parkison syndromes, the
cellular therapy has displayed an inefficiency in dealing with
such problems as incompatible immunology, lack of transplant
organs and absence of graftable cells for several types of human
tissues.
</P>
<P>
Therapeutical cloning, expected to be able to cope with these
problems, will replace the nucleus of ovum with a cell taken from
the patient to be treated and the embryo thus created will only be
used to provide the cells that will later be transplanted back
onto the patient in question. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
