<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greenpeace Urges EU Not to Aid Ukrainian Reactors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The environmentalist group
Greenpeace on Monday urged the European Commission not to finance
Ukraine's nuclear reactors supposed to replace those destroyed by
the 1986 Chernobyl meltdown.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive body of the 15-nation
European Union (EU), is considering a Euratom (European Atomic
Energy Community) loan of 610 million U.S. dollars to the
Ukrainian reactor replacement program.
</P>
<P>
"Europe is still suffering from Chernobyl," said Tobias
Munchmeyer, Greenpeace international nuclear campaigner, adding it
was hardly believable that the commission would support replacing
Chernobyl with two reactors equally dangerous rather than seeking
safer and cheaper energy options.
</P>
<P>
Munchmeyer said that nuclear reactors are never safe and that
the Khmelnitsky 2 and Rovno 4 reactors expected to replace the
Chernobyl reactors cannot reach the highest possible safety
standards as they are of old design and Ukraine lacks the money
for their maintenance.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission is expected to decide on September 6
how to go on with the financing program through the European Bank
for Reconstruction and Development for the Ukrainian nuclear
reactors.
</P>
<P>
The bank itself will finally decide on the loan to the
Ukrainian nuclear reactors later this year.
</P>
<P>
Germany, Austria, Sweden, Denmark and Belgium are formally
opposed to the Ukrainian nuclear reactor program known as the K2R4
project while other EU member states have shown concerns as well,
according to Greenpeace.
</P>
<P>
As most EU countries are opposed to financing K2R4, said
Munchmeyer, the European Commission "must reflect this balance"
and reject any commitment to financing the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0048 </DOCNO>
