</P>
<P>
PARIS -- The metal strip which caused the crash of the Air
France Concorde aircraft on July 25 could have come from a DC10
plane of the U.S. Continental Airlines, the U.S. Continental
Airlines said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. air company said in a communique that the French
Bureau of Accident Investigation (BEA) informed it on September 1
that it would inspect the DC10 plane which made a transit at the
Charles-de-Gaulle-Roissy airport soon before the accident took
place on July 25.
</P>
<P>
The BEA wanted to make sure if the 43-centimeter metal strip
found on the runway of the Concorde was from the DC10. (Concorde-
Crash-Cause)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- The British military mission in Sierra Leone has
expressed optimism that all six soldiers still being held hostage
by the rebel West Side Boys would soon be freed.
</P>
<P>
Talks with the rebel group are progressing well, a spokesman
for the mission was quoted as saying by reports reaching here on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The West Side Boys captured 11 British soldiers on August 25.
Those soldiers were among the hundreds staying in Sierra Leone to
help training the country's national army in the densely-forested
Occra Hills area, about 80 kilometers from the capital Freetown.
(Britain-Sierra Leone-Hostages) 
</P>
</TEXT>
