<HEADLINE> Today's Diplomatic News Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chinese Defense Minister Chi Haotian and Minister of National
Security of Trinidad and Tobago Joseph Theodore held talks here
today.
</P>
<P>
Theodore's visit to China is the first high-level visit of a
Trinidad and Tobago military official to China since the two
countries forged diplomatic ties in 1974.
</P>
<P>
Chi, who is also vice-chairman of the Central Military
Commission and a state councilor, said he believes the friendly
cooperation between the armed forces of the two countries will
score new development in the coming century.
</P>
<P>
 Chinese Vice Premier Meets FAO Director-General
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice Premier Wen Jiabao met with Jacques Diouf,
director-general of the Food and Agricultural Organization of the
United Nations (FAO), and his party today.
</P>
<P>
Wen expressed his gratitude for the FAO and Jacques Diouf's
support for China's agricultural development.
</P>
<P>
He said that there are 800 million people in the world who are
still starving, and that food security is a serious problem facing
the world. He also said that China has achieved the balance
between food supply and demand through decades of effort.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Premier Meets Australian Guests
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Premier Wen Jiabao met with former Australian
Prime Minister John Keating and his party today.
</P>
<P>
Wen expressed his appreciation for Keating's contribution to
promoting Sino-Australian relations. He said China and Australia
have maintained a good relationship since the two countries forged
diplomatic ties in 1972.
</P>
<P>
In particular, he said, during the visit by Chinese President
Jiang Zemin to Australia last year, leaders of the two countries
forged favorable relations for cooperation in the long-term. Since
then, Sino-Australian cooperation in all fields has been further
elevated.
</P>
<P>
 Senior CPC Official Meets Japanese Guests
</P>
<P>
Zeng Qinghong, an alternate member of the Political Bureau of
the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC), met
with Fukushiro Nukaga, former Japanese deputy chief cabinet
secretary, and his party here today.
</P>
<P>
Zeng, who is also a member of the Secretariat of the CPC
Central Committee and head of the Organization Department of the
CPC Central Committee, extended a warm welcome to the Japanese
guests.
</P>
<P>
He said China is the world's largest developing country and
Japan is a major developed country, and it is not only in the
fundamental interest of the two peoples but also conducive to
regional and world peace and prosperity for them to reinforce
cooperation and keep healthy relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
