<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Government Warned of Going Bankrupt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian press Monday warned
that the country's federal government may go bankrupt if it tries
to keep the current wage for its employees under the circumstances
of an oil price fall.
</P>
<P>
The federal government increased the minimum wage for its
government employees from 3500 naira to 7,500 naira (about 110
naira equals to one U. S. dollar) in May this year.
</P>
<P>
The federal government has to pay 400 billion naira per annum
for its workers, while its total income stands at 500 billion
naira if the world oil price could maintain at a high level, said
This Day, a leading Nigerian newspaper. The oil price must not
fall below 25 dollars per barrel, the newspaper said, anything
less will be catastrophic as the government stands the risk of
going bankrupt because the balance of a little over 100 billion
naira will be insufficient to meet other pressing needs like the
development of infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
More than 80 percent of Nigerian federal government's income
comes from oil revenue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
