<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slight Trade Surplus for Euro Zone in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The euro zone enjoyed a
slight trade surplus with the rest of the world in June whereas
the European Union (EU) suffered a big trade deficit, Eurostat
reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Luxembourg-based statistical agency of the EU said that the
11-nation euro zone posted 1.5 billion euro (1.35 billion U.S.
dollars) as trade surplus in June as against 8.4 billion euro (7.
56 billion dollars) in the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
The euro zone has recorded a trade surplus of 1.1 billion euro
(0.99 billion dollars) for the first six months of the year,
compared with 23.6 billion euro (21.2 billion dollars) in the
first half of the year 1999.
</P>
<P>
The fall in value of the single currency did not facilitate the
euro zone trade with the rest of the world, as expected by some
euro observers.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation EU, however, suffered a trade deficit of 5.1
billion euro (4.59 billion dollars) with the rest of the world in
June. The bloc enjoyed a surplus of 2.4 billion euro (2.1 billion
dollars) in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Eurostat said that the EU suffered a trade deficit of 42
billion euro (37.8 billion dollars) in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months last year, the EU had a trade deficit
of 11.1 billion euro (9.99 billion dollars) with the rest of the
world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
