<HEADLINE> Canada Launches Nationwide School Bus Check for Faulty Brakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Canadian inspectors have spent
up to 14 hours a day since the Oregon-based Freightliner Corp.
issued warning Saturday saying 6,000 of the company's school buses
may have defective brakes, members of the school board in the
country said Monday.
</P>
<P>
There have been no cases of accident being linked to the
reported faulty braking systems in Canada. Nor have the inspectors
found major problems so far with the buses, according to the board,
which expects the inspection to be completed by Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The number of Canadian school buses affected by the faulty
component is not known, although inspection is being reported
under way in such major cities as Ottawa, Edmonton and Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
Freightliner Corp. reported that the defect is found in anti-
lock braking systems built between March 1998 and August 2000 by
Bendix Commercial Vehicle Systems of Elyria, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
The defect can cause a temporary failure of the brakes when an
affected school bus is traveling at speeds less than 32 kilometers
an hour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
