<HEADLINE> Moldovan Club Banned by UEFA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- European football's control and
disciplinary committee have banned Moldavan club Chisinau
Constructorul from all European competitions for a year, it was
revealed in Nyon, Switzerland on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The action taken relates to incidents during and after the UEFA
Cup qualifier against Bulgarian side CSKA Sofia on August 10, the
UEFA body said in a statement from their headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The Moldovan club had four players cautioned and two sent off
during the match. In addition, the club president's wife insulted
the UEFA delegate after a penalty had been awarded to the visitors
and, after the match, a member of the club entourage threatened an
assistant referee with a gun while he was sending a fax from the
hotel reception desk.
</P>
<P>
The UEFA committee also suspended Moldovan player Iurii Mirza
for two years and fined the club 8,600 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The disciplinary body also imposed a fine of 28,700 dollars on
Portuguese side FC Porto, after coins, a cigarette lighter and a
stone were thrown at match officials as they returned to the
dressing-rooms after the UEFA Champions League qualifier against
RSC Anderlecht.
</P>
<P>
Dutch club Feyenoord were also sanctioned for similar incidents
during the UEFA Champions League qualifier against Austrian Sturm
Graz. 
</P>
</TEXT>
