<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Contacts for Broad-based Coalition with Likud Underway: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Environment Minister
Dalia Itzik said on Monday that she and other members from the
ruling One Israel bloc have been talking with the opposition Likud
leader Ariel Sharon about forming a national unity government if
peace talks with the Palestinians fall though next month.
</P>
<P>
Itzik told Israel Radio that in her view, the Likud also
understands that the present system does not enable the prime
minister to run the country. She believes that time is ripe to cope
with social issues that have been neglected in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Sharon and other Likud members have rejected the idea of
building a national unity government. Likud Knesset (Parliament)
member Tzabi Hanegbi said that Prime Minister Ehud Barak has not
approached the key opposition party.
</P>
<P>
In a surprise move late August, Barak reached out to the Likud,
saying that if he fails to reach a peace accord with the
Palestinians, he will form a broad government based on his newly
unveiled social "civic agenda."
</P>
<P>
He called the Likud a natural partner and even said Sharon was
qualified for the post of foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Analysts, however, held that Barak might use the Likud's
possible entry into the coalition as a scare tactic to pressure the
Palestinians into showing flexibility in the stalled peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Barak has slowed down his government reshuffle efforts while
waiting for Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat
to demonstrate signs of "flexibility" so as to continue the peace
talks stalled since the July Camp David summit.
</P>
<P>
The Barak government has been severely crippled by the
resignations of three right-wing and religious coalition partners
including the Yisrael Ba'aliya, the National Religious Party and
Shas on the eve of his departure for Camp David, and later by the
resignation of former Foreign Minister David Levy and his Gesher
Party from the ruling coalition One Israel.
</P>
<P>
The government is left with only 40 seats in the 120-member
Knesset.
</P>
<P>
Barak has been unable to decide which parties he will bring into
the coalition as he is yet to determine which direction the
government is going to take.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming U.N. Millenium summit, where he is expected to meet
U.S. President Bill Clinton over the peace process, provides a
crucial opportunity for Barak in terms of the fate of the peace
process and of his government.
</P>
<P>
Officials in Barak's office have said that if Barak is able to
reach an agreement, he will bring it back to the Knesset and
breathe new life into his government. If he comes back empty-
handed, new elections appear almost certain.
</P>
<P>
A senior official close to Barak who is on his way to New York
for the Millenium summit said on Monday that the meetings at the
Millennium summit must not be seen as the final date for
negotiations. He emphasized that there is still time to see if
Israel has a true partner for peace.
</P>
<P>
Only then would Barak start to build a unity government with the
Likud, he added.
</P>
<P>
A trilateral meeting between Clinton, Barak and Arafat has not
been scheduled although Clinton is to meet separately with the two
leaders on Wednesday in a new effort to bridge the gaps between
their positions in the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Barak as well as diplomatic officials have been pessimistic
about the chances of a breakthrough at the U.N. summit, the first
major opportunity for the revival of intensive Israeli-Palestinian
talks following the 15-day Camp David summit, which collapsed due
to differences over the core issues the Israelis and Palestinians
have been trying to settle, particularly the status of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has stressed that any settlement must abide by the U.N.
resolutions which called for Israel's withdrawal from occupied
territories it captured during the 1967 Middle East war, including
East Jerusalem. The Palestinians have been striving to establish an
independent state with East Jerusalem as its capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
