<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey, Romania Sign Protocol on Justice Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Turkey and Romania signed on
Monday a justice cooperation protocol, Anatolia News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The accord, signed by Turkish Justice Minister Hikmet Sami Turk
and his Romanian counterpart Valeriu Stoica, focused on exchange of
information and experience in jurisprudence, education of judges,
prosecutors and other judicial personnel, and preparation of draft
laws.
</P>
<P>
The protocol will be implemented through cooperation programs
that will be prepared annually.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will form expert and working groups to solve
the problems that may occur and to increase the cooperation
programs.
</P>
<P>
The exchange of information will be accelerated by conferences
and seminars that will be jointly held, it said.
</P>
<P>
Following the signing ceremony, Turk said that Turkey and
Romania are two friendly countries which share a common geography
in the Balkans and Black Sea, adding that bilateral relations in
every field will be further improved by this cooperation protocol.
</P>
<P>
The European Union's (EU) acceptance of the two countries as
candidates brought a new dimension to the relations while the
globalization forces all countries to have cooperation with other
countries to fully implement their laws, Turk said.
</P>
<P>
Stoica, who arrived in Ankara Sunday for an official visit, said
that as the members of the Council of Europe (CE), the two
countries has signed several international agreements, adding that
improving cooperation in jurisprudence is important for both sides.
</P>
<P>
Turk indicated that there was no agreement with Romania on the
extradition of political criminals. "The political criminals are
never extradited but there are not any problems in the extradition
of (common) criminals," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
