<HEADLINE> Philippine Peso Falls to 32-month Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine peso ended
weaker on a 32-month low Monday against the U.S. dollar amid
higher demand for the greenback.
</P>
<P>
The peso closed at 45.30 pesos to one dollar, 15 centavos
weaker from last Friday's close of 45.15 pesos.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said there is high demand for dollars, as import
requirements of local manufacturers have started picking up.
</P>
<P>
"There are still many corporate clients buying dollars,
especially because it's the import season, and there's little (
dollar) liquidity in the system," a dealer at a major local bank
said.
</P>
<P>
The unresolved domestic political woes and the softer Thai baht
have also helped dampen sentiment on the local currency.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said currency players prefer holding dollars on
expectations the lingering political unrest in Mindanao would haul
up dollar's value over the peso.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, a bomb blast allegedly set up by the Muslim
separatist group, the Moro Islamic Liberation Front, destroyed an
empty fermentation tank owned by beverage giant San Miguel Corp.
in Davao province.
</P>
<P>
The bandit group Abu Sayyaf also continues to hold six European
hostages and a new American victim at the southern Jolo island.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Governor Rafael Buenaventura of the Central Bank of
the Philippines had consistently denied any intervention at the
spot market despite talks the central bank provided dollar
liquidity to help the peso from sliding further.
</P>
<P>
The peso was traded between the range of 45.18 pesos and 45.30
pesos against the dollar on Monday, with value turnover reaching
76 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
