<HEADLINE> Romania's Interest Rates to Rise As Inflation Mounts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, September 4 (Xinhua) -- As Romania's inflation is
predicted to go up to 37-38 percent this year, the National Bank (
BNR) plans to raise interest rates, the local Ziarul Financiar
daily reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The year-on-year inflation was originally estimated at 27
percent, but such factors as drought and high prices in the
international oil market have pushed it higher. In the first seven
months of the year, the aggregated rate was 24.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
"We do not seek a sudden rise in interest rates, but they must
be adjusted to the new inflation target," BNR Deputy Governor
Cristian Popa was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Interest rates on deposits currently range between 30 percent
and 38 percent, and with the T-bonds, they stand at 40 percent per
annum. Bankers predicted that the interest rates will hit 40-50
percent this autumn.
</P>
<P>
Romania's national currency leu has depreciated by 26.09
percent since the year's beginning, with the dollar quoted at 23,
019 lei at the end of last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
