<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Withdraw From CIS Visa System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Russia on Monday notified the
Executive Committee of the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS)
that it would withdraw from a 1992 agreement on visa-free movement
of CIS citizens.
</P>
<P>
The Bishkek agreement "loses force for Russia 90 days following
the CIS executive committee's receipt of this note," the Interfax
news agency quoted the Russian Foreign Ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov has defended the move,
which was criticized by some other CIS members including Georgia
and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov said the decision was prompted by concerns over the
dangers of international terrorism, drug trafficking and organized
crime.
</P>
<P>
"These dangers compel the Russian leaders to take appropriate
steps," he said.
</P>
<P>
In Tbilisi, Georgian Minister Without Portfolio Malkhaz
Kakabadze said on Sunday that Russia's withdrawal from the visa-
free system would undoubtedly influence the normal functioning of
the CIS.
</P>
<P>
He accused "certain Russian circles" of being no longer
interested in the CIS, Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in an interview with reporters last Friday,
Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma said Russia's withdrawal from
the Bishkek treaty destroys the idea of a CIS free trade zone.
</P>
<P>
"This is Russia's right, but I believe that it should have been
discussed, if we recognize such an instrument as the CIS," Kuchma
said.
</P>
<P>
A free trade zone presupposes "the free movement" of capital,
goods, and people. "If this (free movement) is missing, the idea
of a free trade zone is killed. The question arises: who in this
case needs the CIS?" he said.
</P>
<P>
The CIS includes former Soviet republics Russia, Belarus,
Ukraine, Armenia, Azerbaijan, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Moldova,
Tajikistan, Turkmenistan, Uzbekistan and Georgia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No German Referendum to Be Held on EU's Enlargement: EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
information service on Monday ruled out what the press described
as a panic caused over the weekend by the EU's German commissioner
on the issue of the EU's enlargement.
</P>
<P>
What the commissioner said in a newspaper interview was meant
to get the broadest possible public support for the process of
enlargement, said a spokesman of the European Commission, the
executive body of the 15-nation bloc.
</P>
<P>
"Both Commissioner Guenther Verheugen and the commission only
wish to get the broadest possible support from the citizens in the
EU member states," said spokesman Jean-Christophe Filori.
</P>
<P>
Verheugen told the German newspaper Sueddeutsche Zeitung in an
interview that German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder should ask the
Germans how they feel about the EU's expansion which is expected
to include 13 more countries.
</P>
<P>
Some press took Verheugen's remark as calling for a referendum
in Germany on the issue of enlargement.
</P>
<P>
Filori denied that the commissioner called for a referendum in
his interview with the newspaper, saying that both the
commissioner and the commission wanted to strengthen the process
of enlargement which already went well under way.
</P>
<P>
In August, the EU started a publicity campaign for the
enlargement.
</P>
<P>
The EU began talks in 1998 with Hungary, Poland, the Czech
Republic, Estonia, Slovenia and Cyprus on their entry into the
union.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria, Romania, Latvia, Lithuania, Slovakia and Malta have
been added to the applicant country list and started accession
negotiations. Turkey is also on the list but will enter
negotiations in several years.
</P>
<P>
Romano Prodi, president of the European Commission, has asked
the commissioner for an explanation on his remarks to the German
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Verheugen will also explain to Prodi as well as to the
applicant countries, said Filori.
</P>
<P>
Jonathan Faull, chief spokesman of the commission, said on
Monday that EU enlargement is the greatest task for the current
commission and perhaps the greatest task for the current
generation of Europeans as well.
</P>
<P>
Yet he added how enlargement is done depends on the
institutional mechanism of individual member state.
</P>
<P>
A recent EU survey showed that around 68 percent of the Germans
feel the EU's eastward expansion is not a priority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UEFA Clears Main Moldova Stadium for Internationals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Moldova has been given permission
by UEFA to use their main stadium for international matches this
season, the country's soccer chief said in Chisinau, Moldova.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year UEFA slapped an international ban on the
Republic Stadium in Chisinau because of a lack of proper media
facilities, toilets and changing rooms.
</P>
<P>
Pavel Ciobanu, president of the Moldovan Football Federation (
MFF), said: "We had a UEFA commission visiting the stadium last
week and they approved all the necessary repairs.
</P>
<P>
"Now I can assure you that our national team will play its
World Cup qualifiers this season here in Chisinau."
</P>
<P>
Moldova, who lost 2-0 away to Turkey in a World Cup match on
Saturday, will take on Slovakia on October 7 in Chisinau in
European group four, which also includes Sweden, Macedonia and
Azerbaijan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
