<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Parliamentary Delegation Visits Poland to Cement Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 4 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi National Assembly
(parliament) delegation left here on Monday for Poland, aiming to
strengthen relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Ghalib Al-Jasim, National Assembly secretary and also head of
the delegation, said in a statement that during the visit, he will
hold talks with the speaker and other members of the Polish
parliament to boost ties between the two parliaments.
</P>
<P>
He will also meet Polish ministers of foreign affairs,
agriculture, health and higher education to discuss ways to promote
bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will brief the Polish side on Iraq's stance on
international issues, Al-Jasim said, adding that Iraq will stress
the necessity of observing the international norms "to guarantee
the interests of all states."
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi-Polish relations have witnessed improvement in recent
months.
</P>
<P>
Polish Ministry of Economy Undersecretary Tadeusz Donocik
visited Iraq at the end of July and held talks with Iraqi Trade
Minister Mohammad Mehdi Salah, Minister of Industry and Minerals
Adnan Abd Al-Majid Jasim Al-Ani, and Irrigation Minister Mahmoud
Diyab Al-Ahmad.
</P>
<P>
The Polish official said that Poland is keen to develop trade
ties with Iraq to make up for the heavy losses it suffered in trade
dealings with the country during the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade exchanges, which used to be more than 500
million U.S. dollars, almost came to a standstill after the United
Nations imposed stringent sanctions on Iraq for its 1990 invasion
of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Poland is just one of the European countries which have been
developing trade relations with Iraq under the U.N. oil-for-food
program in order to gain a slice of Iraq's lucrative reconstruction
market, estimated at about 200 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. humanitarian program allows Iraq to sell oil under U.N.
supervision to buy humanitarian supplies to alleviate the crippling
impacts of the sanctions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
