<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Opens Domestic Telecoms Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Communications
Minister Binyamin Ben Eliezer Monday signed a series of regulations
to open Israel's domestic telecommunications market to competition.
</P>
<P>
The statutes, approved in a vote by Israeli Knesset's
(Parliament) Finance Committee members early Monday, are aiming to
end the market monopoly by the state-owned Bezeq, or Israeli
Telecom company.
</P>
<P>
At a specially-arranged press conference, Ben Eliezer said that
the signing of the statutes ushers in a new era which will give
Israeli citizens a greater choice in all telecommunications fields
as well as better service and prices.
</P>
<P>
"Today I can appear before you and say that the era of
monopolies is over," said Ben Eliezer. "Today we are firing the
starting pistol to open competition in the field of
telecommunications in Israel."
</P>
<P>
He said that any company which wants to enter the market could
apply for licenses from his ministry, providing that the company is
registered in Israel with 20 percent of it controlled by Israeli
residents, has experience in operating telecommunications systems
and has at least 60 million U.S. dollars in capital.
</P>
<P>
Once getting the license approval, the company should begin its
service in 12 months, according to ministry officials. The licenses
will last for 15 years with an option for a 10-year extension.
</P>
<P>
Israel's cable television companies, which have essential
infrastructure to compete with Bezeq in the market, might be the
most likely capable competitor to Bezeq in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Ben Eliezer promised to remove the obstacles for cable companies
to enter the market in the next two or three months, referring to
the ban imposed by the government on these companies' entering the
market.
</P>
<P>
Another regulation, from which Israeli net surfers could
benefit, will allow Bezeq to provide high-speed Internet service to
Israeli households in the nearest future.
</P>
<P>
Israeli antitrust authorities earlier ruled that Bezeq should
not be allowed to begin the service before any competitors could
get a foothold.
</P>
<P>
However, Ben Eliezer said Monday that considering the public's
demand, he preferred to grant Bezeq a license for the service in
the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
Bezeq's ADSL (Asymmetrical Digital Subscriber Loop) technology
will allow net surfers to enjoy fast downloads of music files and
video clips from the Internet at high bandwidth on existing phone
lines.
</P>
<P>
Cable companies are also expected to enter the high-speed
Internet service market through their cable lines.
</P>
<P>
However, some analysts also warned that the approval of
deregulation in the telecommunications market will not make the
market inundated with dozens of new companies within days. The
process, they argued, could last for at least 12 months, or even
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
