<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Attracts 1.5 Million Tourists in First Half Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 4 (Xinhua) -- More than 1.5 million
tourists poured into Israel for sightseeing in the first half of
the year, official statistics showed.
</P>
<P>
And even better times are expected for the Israeli tourism next
year, given the bookings, particularly if the peace process
continues, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The first six months saw a 30-percent rise in tourism as
compared to the same period last year, the Ha'aretz newspaper
quoted official statistics as saying on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Among the 1.4 million tourists arriving in Israel (excluding
visitors participating in cruises), nearly 280,000 came from the
United States, up 14 percent since 1999.
</P>
<P>
The share of the Israeli tourist market from North America,
including Mexico, during the first half of the year, stood at 26
percent.
</P>
<P>
Europeans held a 64 percent share of Israel's tourism during the
same period. Most were from Germany, 114,809 in all, accounting for
8 percent of the total for the period and an increase of 28 percent
over last year.
</P>
<P>
One source to tourism to Israel which witnessed a decline in
figures was Russia. The figures dropped from 25,552 during the
first part of the last year to 18,675 this year, a 27 percent
decline.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is one of the pillar industries of Israel which is rich
in holy sites.
</P>
<P>
In mid-August, Israel reacted strongly to a U.S. statement
warning its citizens over the increase of terrorist threats and
safety concerns in the region, fearing that the warning might
negatively affect the country's tourism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Accession to WTO to Boost HK Economy, Economist  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 4 (Xinhua) -- A senior financial official
said Monday that the considerable increase in business on China's
mainland expected to result from its prospective entry into the
World Trade Organization (WTO) will eventually boost Hong Kong's
economy.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Yam, chief executive of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority,
made the remarks at a conference on globalization, addressing the
implications for Hong Kong of China's accession to the WTO laying
particular stress on the likely effects on Hong Kong's financial
and banking sector and the question of monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
"Our estimates within the authority suggest that our re-export
trade, involving the movement of goods to and from the mainland
through Hong Kong, will be considerably boosted, and should raise
our annual GDP growth rate by somewhere between 0.5 percent and
one percent," Yam said.
</P>
<P>
According to Yam, the stimulus to liberalization, globalization
and better corporate governance will expand and deepen Hong Kong's
well-established role as a fund of professional expertise, a
center of international experience, and a source and channel of
investment.
</P>
<P>
Yam noted that Hong Kong's banking sector, with its strong
reputation and long involvement in mainland business, stands to
benefit greatly from the liberalization in this area, providing
that it can position itself to make the best out of the
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
"As the largest source of foreign direct investment in the
mainland, and as China's main financial conduit and funding center,
Hong Kong will stand to benefit considerably from the increased
demand for banking services in China," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
In the monetary sphere, the various predictions about the
future development of the Renminbi (Chinese currency) in the light
of WTO membership would most likely have positive implications for
Hong Kong's economy as a whole, Yam concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Shares Prices Firm Led by Blue-chips </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Share prices closed higher
on Singapore Stock Market Monday lifted by buying of select blue-
chip stocks.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index rose 29.36 points, or 1.4
percent, to end at 2,190.06 points in light trading.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume remained weak at 226.64 million units
worth 374.16 million Singapore dollars (about 218.81 million U.S.
dollars). Gainers led losers by 191 to 109 with 269 counters
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Mylect topped the volume list with a turnover of 25.50 million
units. Reed was the second heavily traded stock with 14.28 million
shares traded. Li Xin was the next with 10.87 million counters
changing hands.
</P>
<P>
DBS and SPH led the advancing issues of the day picking up 70
cents each to close at 21.90 and 28.10 Singapore dollars
respectively. SPH 100 moved up 60 cents to finish at 28.20
Singapore dollars. PacCent edged up 50 cents to finish at 23.70
Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
DBS DBECw02 headed the descent of the day shedding 20 cents to
close at 1.90 Singapore dollars. JurCem retreated 14 cents to
finish at 1.81 Singapore dollars. Venture dropped 10 cents to end
at 22.10 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the STI surged past the 2180-point key
resistance level, but failed to breach the psychological 2200-
point support level.
</P>
<P>
The DBS-50 Index, which gives greater weighting to the largest
stocks and excludes foreign-currency issues, rose 10.30 points, or
1.5 percent, to 709.57 points.
</P>
<P>
Trading volume remained thin as investors awaited the return of
U.S. fund managers after the Labor Day holiday Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
