<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Launches Programs to Speed up Economic Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
officially announced here Monday the programs to speed up economic
recovery process in the country.
</P>
<P>
Coordinating Minister for Economic Affairs Rizal Ramli told a
press conference, the programs consist of ten points which among
other things are creating the financial stability, increasing the
people's social welfare, developing small and medium industries,
increasing farmers welfare and productivity, prioritizing the
equity-based recovery, increasing exports, launching the value-
creation privatization programs, carrying out the economic
decentralization as well as safeguarding fiscal balancing,
optimizing the use of natural resources and accelerating the
corporate and banking restructuring programs.
</P>
<P>
Ramli said the programs will also be outlined in detail under
the new memorandum on the financial and economic policies or so
called the letter of intent (LoI) that is due to be signed by the
government and the International Monetary Fund (IMF) on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Today, we announce what we said as ten points of programs for
the acceleration of economic recovery. And the IMF has agreed to
include such programs in the new LoI. And I also hope that the
parliament will also give its support to the programs," Ramli said.
</P>
<P>
He was optimistic that with the implementation of the programs,
the economic recovery process could be accelerated.
</P>
<P>
Ramli said that in a bid to boost efforts in creating financial
stability, his side will strengthen cooperation with the country's
central bank.
</P>
<P>
"We will synchronize our policies with the central bank (
policies) to avoid overlapping," he said, adding the economic team
will also try to improve the market confidence in the national
economic recovery programs.
</P>
<P>
"In term of exports, we hope that the national exports will
become a second locomotive for the economic recovery after
consumption," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, based on a report issued by the National Bureau of
Statistic (BPS), the country's export in July reached its all-time
high with a record of 5.353 billion U.S. dollars or 1.17 percent
higher than the figure in June when it stood at 5.291 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Bureau also disclosed that during January-July this year,
the country's export value reached 34.653 billion dollars or up by
33.68 percent against the same period last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
