<HEADLINE> Xinhua Asia-Pacific Economic News Summary, Monday, September 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING -- China is assured of self-sufficiency of grain supply
despite increasing pressure of population growth, China Daily
reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the English-language newspaper, China is expected
to import 20 million to 30 million tons of grain every year in the
first decades of the 21 century.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that that by using advanced farming
techniques, the country will be able to increase grain output per
hectare by 1.5 tons.
</P>
<P>
---
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thailand's inflation rate is increasing as higher
crude oil prices pushed up retail prices of gasoline and diesel
and increased electricity costs and food prices, a report from the
government said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The consumer price index, the broadest gauge of inflation, rose
O.6 percent in August from the previous month, the biggest monthly
increase since April 1998, it said.
</P>
<P>
The government will try to limit price increases to a maximum
of 2.2 percent for the full year through price controls and
informal requests to vendors, the report said.
</P>
<P>
---
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- India's inflation rate fell below the six percent
level to stand at 5.73 percent during the week ended August 19, an
official release said here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate fell to 5.73 percent from the level of 6.03
percent in the previous week mainly due to a decline in the prices
of non-food articles, said the release.
</P>
<P>
---
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thailand's economic growth rate this year would not
be lower than 4.1 percent, The Thai News Agency (TNA) reported on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Chatumongkol Sonakul, the Governor of The Bank of Thailand (BOT)
, the country's central bank, was quoted as saying that Thailand's
economic growth rate this year would not be lower than 4.1 percent,
despite a current oil price hike.
</P>
<P>
---
</P>
<P>
YANGON -- Myanmar will hold this year's mid-year gems emporium,
which is the ninth of its kind, on October 3 to put on sale
locally-produced gems, pearl and jewelry through competitive
bidding or tender, official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
---
</P>
<P>
CHANGSHA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A bullet-shaped locomotive
designed with a maximum speed of 305 km per hour, the highest
locomotive so far in China, came off the production line Sunday in
the Zhuzhou Locomotive Plant in central China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
The electric-powered train engine called "Lanjian" (Blue Arrow)
has been designated as one of China's key technological research
programs. Ten academicians from the Chinese Academy of Engineering
(CAE) observed the production with engineers and experts from the
plant here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The train will be put into use on the Guangzhou-Shenzhen line
in south China's Guangdong Province next year.
</P>
<P>
---
</P>
<P>
CHANGCHUN -- The manufacture of China's first magnetic
suspension train for commercial operation is expected to be
completed by the end of October this year.
</P>
<P>
The magnetic suspension train is being constructed by the
Changchun Passenger Railway Car Plant in northeast China's Jilin
Province. It consists of one trailer and two headstocks with
control rooms.
</P>
<P>
The 11.2-meter-long train weighs 18 tons. The train carrying
about 80 passengers will be raised eight mm high above the rails
and travel at a speed of 80 kilometers per hour.
</P>
<P>
---
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- The Philippine government said Monday it has the
capacity to finance the budget deficit which shot up to 59.7
billion pesos (1.49 billion U.S. dollars) as of July against a
full-year target of 62.5 billion pesos (1.56 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
This position was made by National Treasurer Leonor Briones to
downplay reports that the government may incur more than the
target deficit set by the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
Briones said that the financial situation in the country is
strong because the domestic market is liquid at this time
considering that there are more fund inflows brought about by the
raising of the proceeds from the privatization bonds amounting to
8 billion pesos (200 million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
