<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Wants Non-Trade Barriers Removed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Monday suggested
that the non-trade barriers be removed first between ASEAN and
Australia/New Zealand, which is known as Closer Economic Relation
(CER).
</P>
<P>
A special task force is studying the possibility of setting up
a free trade area (FTA) between the two groupings.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian International Trade and Industry Minister Rafidah
Aziz proposed that the special task force focus on removing the
non-trade barriers and look at facilitating trade between the two
groupings as a short-term measure as efforts to establish a FTA
will take time.
</P>
<P>
"Removing trade barriers would require time as it involves
further negotiations on the mechanism for the free trade area,"
Rafidah told reporters after meeting New Zealand's Minister for
Trade Negotiations, Rural Affairs and Agriculture, Jim Sutton,
here.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is less concerned over removing the trade barriers
since 60 percent of its goods are already on the zero-duty list,
she said.
</P>
<P>
"We are more concerned on the removal of non-trade barriers
which hinder the smooth flow of goods and services between the two
groupings," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
She said ASEAN was currently fully occupied with the process of
implementing AFTA (ASEAN Free Trade Area) rather than focusing on
establishing FTA between AFTA and CER.
</P>
<P>
The task force, set up after the ASEAN Economic Ministers
Meeting (AEM) in Singapore in September 1999, is scheduled to
table its study and recommendations for consideration at the next
AEM in Thailand this October.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Cambodia, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia,
Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southeast Asia-Motor Sales Show Strong Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Southeast Asian motorcycle
sales demonstrated a strong recovery to increase 54.3 percent in
the first seven months on a year-on-year basis, according to a
report from Honda Motor Company's regional headquarters here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Total sales in the Southeast Asian market during the January-to-
July period recorded at 1.15 million units, with Thailand
maintaining its position as the region's largest motorcycle market,
followed by Indonesia, Malaysia and the Philippines, it said.
</P>
<P>
Noting the regional growth is largely powered by a 101.6
percent increase in Indonesia, it said if the Indonesian sales
continue to grow, it is likely to take Thailand's place as the
world's third-largest motorcycle market, after China and India, at
the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Based on the current sales trends, it expected that the total
Southeast Asian motorcycle sales this year is likely to reach 2.7
million units, up 80 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
The regional sales have peaked in 1997 with total sales of 3.3
million units, but severely decreased in 1998 and 1999 due to the
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
In Thailand, Honda company still led the market share of 30
percent, followed by Kawasaki, Yamaha and Suzuki, it added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
