<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investors' Share Accounts for 7.8 percent of S. Korea's GDP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The share by foreign investors
in South Korea's gross domestic product (GDP) hit 7.8 percent in
1999, up from 2.6 percent in 1996, the South Korean Maeil Business
Newspaper said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said foreigner investors are responsible for 30-
percent of the local stock market's capitalization and their
contribution to the economy has been on a steady rise.
</P>
<P>
Sales by South Korean firms with foreign stock ownership
surpassing 50 percent grew to 18.5 percent in the manufacturing
sector in 1999, up from 5.5 percent in 1996 before a financial
crisis hit the country in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
Those firms also saw their value-added and job creation rates
rise to 21.2 percent and 9.7 percent from 4.6 percent and 3.8
percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government said the ratio of foreign
investments against GDP remain at a low level, compared with the
worldwide average of 11.7 percent in the same year.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Commerce, Industry and Energy wishes to raise
the GDP portion of foreign investments to around 20 percent, said
the paper.
</P>
<P>
However, some South Korean experts are concerned about the
widening gap between foreign owned firms and South Korean firms as
the former registered a growth of ordinary profits at an average
11.7 percent in 1999 while the latter recorded a 1.1-percent loss
in ordinary profits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
