<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Metal Strip Causing Crash of Concorde Could Have Come from U.S. Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The metal strip which caused the
crash of the Air France Concorde aircraft on July 25 could have
come from a DC10 plane of the U.S. Continental Airlines, the U.S.
Continental Airlines said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. air company said in a communique that the French
Bureau of Accident Investigation (BEA) informed it on September 1
that it would inspect the DC10 plane which made a transit at the
Charles-de-Gaulle-Roissy airport soon before the accident took
place on July 25.
</P>
<P>
The BEA wanted to make sure if the 43-centimeter metal strip
found on the runway of the Concorde was from the DC10.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of Continental and officials from BEA and the U.S.
National Transportation Safety Board which is the U.S. counterpart
of BEA inspected the plane on Saturday in Houston and found that a
metal strip "of a shape similar" with the metal strip suspected to
have caused the crash of the Concorde was missing from the plane,
said Continental Airlines.
</P>
<P>
But it is not determined so far whether the metal strip found
on the runway was really from the DC10 or not, it said.
</P>
<P>
The metal strip could have punctured a tire on the
undercarriage of the Concorde, resulting in a chain reaction
including the fire which broke out on the rear part of the plane.
</P>
<P>
The Concorde crash killed 113 people, most of them German
tourists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
