<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Archaeology News: Weekly Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The following is a round-up of
China's archaeology news for the past week:
</P>
<P>
-- China Discovers 2,000-Year-Old Well
</P>
<P>
An ancient well with more than 2,000 years of history was
recently discovered in the northern suburbs of Fuzhou, capital of
east China's Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
The well was discovered in the ruins of an ancient city named
Xindian, where archaeologists also discovered a group of ancient
buildings dating back to the Western Han Dynasty (206 B.C. to 14 A.
D.).
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists unearthed a number of daily-life potteries that
included cups, bowls, kettles, pots and urns.
</P>
<P>
-- Excavation Proves Yangling Mausoleum Built by Prisoners
</P>
<P>
Archeological excavations at the Yangling Mausoleum in
northwest China's Shaanxi Province showed that this underground
palace was built by some 10,000 prisoners.
</P>
<P>
The discovery was made by a farmer in Xianyang, where 27 tombs
dating back to the Han (206 B.C.-220 A.D.) and Tang (A.D. 618-907)
dynasties were found. The farmer found a great amount of bones
scattered underground on a piece of land near the Yangling
Mausoleum when he dug a reservoir.
</P>
<P>
Further excavation showed that the place had been a graveyard
for more than 10,000 mausoleum builders, whose heads and bodies
were buried in different places.
</P>
<P>
-- Ancient Tombs Discovered in Beijing
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists have discovered an unusual group of 72
tombs in Beijing's eastern suburbs, with the earliest dating back
to 2,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The graveyard is the biggest of its kind found in the Chinese
capital, the archaeologists said, adding that they might lead to
the discovery of a big ruined city in Yanqing, Beijing's satellite
city.
</P>
<P>
Most of the tombs belonged to the Han Dynasty (206 B.C.- 220 A.
D.) and Tang Dynasty (A.D. 618-906), from which the archaeologists
have unearthed some pottery and iron and bronze vessels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Archaeology News: Weekly Briefs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- Neolithic Period Relics Unearthed in Shaanxi
</P>
<P>
A group of porcelain wares, bone and stone tools from the
Neolithic period were unearthed recently in Huangling County in Xi
'an, capital of northwest China's Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The relics include spicules, each 13 centimeters long and in
the shaped like an elephant's tooth. The stone knives are well
polished and quite sharp.
</P>
<P>
The relics were excavated at the ruins of Longshan Culture
which existed in the New Stone Age. Experts said they are of great
value in studying human activities during the pre-history period.
</P>
<P>
-- Beijing Repairs Wall of Ancient Altar
</P>
<P>
Beijing started repairing the broken wall of the Temple of
Heaven, China's largest and best-reserved imperial altar built in
the early 15th century.
</P>
<P>
The repairing project, which will cost five million yuan, is
expected to restore the northwestern section of the fence by the
end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The repaired part will be 780 meters and five meters high and
is expected to be linked with the remained northern section.
</P>
<P>
-- Int'l Cliff Painting Symposium Opens
</P>
<P>
The Second Ningxia International Cliff Painting Symposium was
organized recently in Yinchuan, capital of northwest China's
Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
More than 130 sculptors and experts from 13 countries attended
the opening ceremony. Cliff paining, as one of the most popular
form of arts in the world, has been discovered in over 120
countries. China has found thousands of cliff paintings in over 20
provinces.
</P>
<P>
Helan Mountain alone, once a nomadic area, is the home to
thousands of cliff paintings carved by nomads in northern China
some 2,000 years ago. They are scattered over an area stretching
several hundred of kilometers.
</P>
<P>
-- China to Build National Reclamation Museum
</P>
<P>
China plans to build a national reclamation museum to exhibit
the history of cultivation on the western frontier.
</P>
<P>
The museum is based on an existing local reclamation museum in
Shihezi City, Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
A total of 50 million yuan (about 6.1 million U.S. dollars)
will be poured into the museum whose construction will start next
year. The museum will be open to the public in two years.
</P>
<P>
The People's Liberation Army (PLA) started to reclaim wasteland
in Xinjiang in 1949. Up till now, the Xinjiang Production and
Construction Corps have 150 farms, with a population of 2.2
million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
