<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Acting FM Abroad on Secret Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli acting Foreign
Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami had left the country for secret
negotiations abroad, officials with the Foreign Ministry confirmed
Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
The officials refused to reveal Ben-Ami's destination and any
other details, only saying that his travels are related to the
ongoing peace talks between Israel and the Palestinians.It appears,
according to a report on Israel's Ha'aretz daily's website, that
Ben-Ami has gone to an Arab country for secret talks.
</P>
<P>
Ben-Ami, who also holds the Public Security portfolio, took over
the foreign ministry after his predecessor David Levy resigned in
the wake of Camp David peace summit in July.
</P>
<P>
He had played an active role in the talks in May when he and
Palestinian Legislative Council Speaker Ahmed Qurei (Abu Ala)
launched the so-called "back-channel" negotiations in Stockholm.
</P>
<P>
He also participated in the U.S.-sponsored Camp David talks,
which was attended by Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak,
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and U.S. President Bill Clinton.
The summit failed to reach any agreement after 15-day-long
exhausting talks.
</P>
<P>
Since the summit failure, Ben-Ami and Israeli Regional
Cooperation Minister Shimon Peres had spearheaded Israel's
worldwide campaign to explicate to world leaders Israeli stands on
all core issues between Israel and the Palestinians, especially on
the thorniest issue of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Barak had arrived in New York to attend the United Nations'
Millennium Summit there. He is scheduled to hold meetings with
Clinton, who will later meet with Arafat separately.
</P>
<P>
These meetings are widely regarded as the last chance for
reviving Israeli-Palestinian talks in the next few weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
