<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Communications Minister Binyamin Ben Eliezer is
expected to sign the long-awaited regulations on Monday that will
open the domestic telecommunications market to competition and lay
down provisions for high-speed Internet.
</P>
<P>
The signing comes as the government moves toward the
privatization of the state telecommunications Bezeq company,
intended to weaken the monopoly it has held on the
telecommunications market.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said during the weekly
cabinet meeting on Sunday that Lebanese parliamentary elections
mark a change in direction that will help diminish Syria's
influence in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The poll is the first tangible evidence of the changes wrought
by Israel's unilateral withdrawal from southern Lebanon in May, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Noting that some 100 days have passed since the Israeli pullout,
Barak said there were hope and opportunity now for relations with
Lebanon as well as Syria, which still maintains a presence of some
30,000 soldiers in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Former leader of the Israeli ultra-Orthodox Shas party Aryeh
Deri began serving his three-year prison sentence at Ma'asiyahu
Prison in Ramla in the midwest part of the country as the first ex-
minister in Israeli history to go to jail.
</P>
<P>
Deri, convicted of bribery, fraud and breach of trust, arrived
at the prison two hours late accompanied by thousands of
supporters, including Shas spiritual leader Rabbi Ovadia Yosef.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak Sunday night left for New
York to attend the U.N. Millennium Summit after telling his cabinet
that he would make use of the meeting to determine whether
Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat is willing to
show any more flexibility since the failed Camp David peace talks
in July.
</P>
<P>
Barak is expected to discuss the peace talks stalemate when he
meets U.S. President Bill Clinton, who is also to meet Arafat
during the U.N. summit which will attract some 160 world leaders.
</P>
