<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strong Demand Keeps Turkish Inflation at High Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- A strong domestic demand
continued to fuel inflation in Turkey, pushing the monthly
wholesale prices index (WPI) and consumer prices index (CPI)
respectively at a high of 0.9 percent and 2.2 percent in August.
</P>
<P>
The figures, published by the State Institute of Statistics on
Sunday, sent the eight-month inflation of this year to 20.9 percent
on the WPI, above a year-end target of 20 percent and to 23.1
percent on the CPI, slightly below the government's 25 percent
year-end target.
</P>
<P>
According to the current figures, the year-on-year WPI and CPI
were expected to remain at a high of 48.9 percent and 53.2 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is implementing a three-year economic stability program
under the 4-billion-U.S.-dollar stand-by deal signed with the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) last December.
</P>
<P>
Under the three-year IMF loan package, Turkey pledged to reduce
its chronic inflation and budget deficits, undertake a
comprehensive privatization program and reform agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The government aims to reduce inflation to 20 percent in 2000,
10 percent in 2001 and 5.0 percent in 2002. The annual inflation
rate stood at 68.9 percent at the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
Despite the August figures, Turkish officials said that it was
unnecessary to revise this year's target because the inflation was
on the down trend.
</P>
<P>
Actually, the figures were at the lower end of market
expectations and would be perceived as good news.
</P>
<P>
Economists argued, however, the CPI figure would provide a
further excuse for the government and the IMF to worry about
growing domestic demand, and look for a set of fiscal tightening
measures in order to cool the economy and avoid inflationary
pressures.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's gross national product (GNP) posted a robust 4.4
percent growth in the second quarter of this year, against a 3.2
percent contraction in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
A pent-up consumer demand and falling interest rates have
boosted consumption in the first six months of the IMF-sponsored
anti-inflation program. Turkey posted a gross domestic product
(GDP) growth of 5.7 percent in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
IMF's Turkey desk chief Carlo Cottarelli said that the economic
program may need some fine tuning, after seeing growth and current
account balance data.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's current account balance has been worsening in the face
of a surge in imports and reached 5.6 billion dollars in the first
six months.
</P>
<P>
Economists have been suggesting that measures are needed to
contain the current account deficit, at least for next year. A
possible package of fine-tuning measures would therefore serve both
ends.
</P>
<P>
Inflation in September and October is seasonally high and will
be a harder test of the government's disinflation program,
economists argued. Monthly inflation has averaged about 6 percent
in September in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The national support behind the anti-inflation economic package
of the government has dipped to a mere 11.7 percent. A recent poll
showed that 80.9 percent of Turks no longer believe that the
government can pull down the annual inflation rate to around 20
percent as it had pledged when launching the anti-inflation
economic package.
</P>
<P>
While 46.1 percent of the group interviewed said that they
wanted the government just to continue implementing the program,
almost equally, 40.3 percent said that they wanted the program
shelved and 13.6 percent were undecided. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fresh Fighting Kills 160 Rebels in Northern Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan Defense
Ministry said Monday that at least 160 Tamil Tiger rebels have
been killed in the northern Jaffna peninsula as the military
launched a fresh offensive.
</P>
<P>
A ministry spokesman said ground troops have observed more than
80 bodies of rebels during the operation on Sunday and the
estimated number of rebels killed is at least 160.
</P>
<P>
He said eight officers and 63 soldiers were killed in the
offensive, while 225 soldiers were wounded. Another 254 soldiers
were treated for minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
Heavily armed soldiers advanced into territory held by the
separatist Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) at Sarasalai,
Maduvil and Nunavil in the Jaffna peninsula on Sunday, said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He said the aim of the operation is to provide more protection
for Jaffna town, which has been surrounded by the rebels since
they captured large amounts of territory in the area early this
year.
</P>
<P>
The army began its assault with heavy bombardment by multiple
rocket launchers. Numerous high-ranking military officials are
reported to have gone to Jaffna from Colombo to supervise the
operation.
</P>
<P>
There was no immediate reaction from the LTTE to the casualty
claim.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels said in a statement from their London office on
Sunday that more than 100 government troops have died and several
hundred more have been injured. They said thousands of civilians
have been forced to flee their homes.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels are fighting for an independent homeland for
minority Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and east since 1983.
</P>
<P>
The new wave of fighting ended a four-month lull in fighting in
the Jaffna Peninsula. In April, the rebels captured Elephant Pass -
- the only land route to the Jaffna Peninsula. The government has
been under pressure to gain ground in the war since then.
</P>
<P>
The military in recent weeks have boosted its firepower with
new combat aircraft and field guns ahead of an anticipated
showdown with the rebels prior to parliamentary polls on October
10.
</P>
<P>
The latest fighting came as political parties prepared to hand
in their election nominations which closed at noon Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
