<HEADLINE> Thailand to Hold Talks With OPEC On Oil Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Thailand, which currently
chairs the United Nations Conference on Trade and Development (
UNCTAD), is considering to hold talks with the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) directly to discuss impacts
of surging oil prices on economies of developing countries, the
Thai News Agency (TNA) reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Secretary to Thai Foreign Minister Nopadol Pattama was quoted
as saying that the Thai government was considering to address the
problem of current oil price hike at its cause by asking the OPEC
to increase its oil production to reduce oil prices in the world
market and to ease difficulties of countries around the world,
particularly developing countries whose economic recovery and
development are now affected by surging oil prices over the past
months.
</P>
<P>
Thailand, which currently chairs the UNCTAD, is considering to
hold talks with the OPEC directly to discuss impacts of the
current oil price surge on the economic recovery and development
of countries around the world, particularly developing nations, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Prime Minister and Commerce Minister Supachai
Panitchpakdi, who currently chairs the UNCTAD and will be Director
of The World Trade Organization (WTO) over the next two years,
would be authorized to discuss the issue with OPEC chiefs, he
stated.
</P>
<P>
The planned talks between Thailand and the OPEC was expected to
be taken place very soon, as the oil producing countries were
scheduled to meet in Vienna on September 10 to review world oil
situation, he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
