<HEADLINE> Manila Vows to Finance Budget Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Monday it has the capacity to finance the budget deficit which
shot up to 59.7 billion pesos (1.49 billion U.S. dollars) as of
July against a full-year target of 62.5 billion pesos (1.56
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
This position was made by National Treasurer Leonor Briones to
downplay reports that the government may incur more than the
target deficit set by the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
Briones said that the financial situation in the country is
strong because the domestic market is liquid at this time
considering that there are more fund inflows brought about by the
raising of the proceeds from the privatization bonds amounting to
8 billion pesos (200 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
There are also other sources of revenues which the government
can tap to make the financial system liquid, the Bureau of the
Treasury official said.
</P>
<P>
One of which is the full implementation of the small-
denominated treasury bonds at the local bourses within this month.
When put on streams, this project could earn for the government an
estimated 30 billion pesos (750 million dollars) in proceeds.
</P>
<P>
Another source, she said, is the scheduled privatization of
three big tickets items of the national government -- the stakes
in the Philippine National Bank, the Philippine National
Construction Corporation, and the Manila Electric Company.
</P>
<P>
This effort could possibly earn for the government about 22
billion pesos (550 million dollars) in proceeds from the sale of
these assets, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
