<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Rebels Suffer Heavy Casualties in Fresh Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 4 (Xinhua) -- At least 216 Tamil Tiger
rebels have been killed in Sri Lanka's northern Jaffna peninsula
as the military launched a fresh offensive, a government spokesman
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Director of Information Ariya Rubasinghe said those rebels were
killed during the confrontations with troops on Sunday in
Colombuturai, Sarasalai, Maduvil and Nunavil.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 rebels of Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE)
were wounded in the fighting, he said, adding that troops are
consolidating the newly captured areas in Colombuturai.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Monday, the Defense Ministry said eight officers and
63 soldiers were killed in the offensive, while 225 soldiers were
wounded. Another 254 soldiers were treated for minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
The operation aims at providing more protection for Jaffna town,
which has been surrounded by the rebels since they captured large
amounts of territory in the area early this year.
</P>
<P>
The army began its assault with heavy bombardment by multiple
rocket launchers. Numerous high-ranking military officials are
reported to have gone to Jaffna from Colombo to supervise the
operation.
</P>
<P>
There was no immediate reaction from the LTTE to the casualty
claim.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels said in a statement from their London office on
Sunday that more than 100 government troops have died and several
hundred more have been injured. They said thousands of civilians
have been forced to flee their homes.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels are fighting for an independent homeland for
minority Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and east since 1983.
</P>
<P>
The new wave of fighting ended a four-month lull in fighting in
the Jaffna Peninsula. In April, the rebels captured Elephant Pass -
the only land route to the Jaffna Peninsula. The government has
been under pressure to gain ground in the war since then.
</P>
<P>
The military in recent weeks had boosted its firepower with new
combat aircraft and field guns ahead of an anticipated showdown
with the rebels prior to parliamentary polls on October 10.
</P>
<P>
The latest fighting came as political parties prepared to hand
in their election nominations which closed at noon Monday.
</P>
