<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Hopes to Resume Talks With MILF Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government hopes
to resume the stalled peace negotiations with the Moro Islamic
Liberation Front (MILF) this week in the southern Cotabato City,
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a radio interview, Zamora said the government has suggested
to the MILF that the meeting would resume either September 7 or 8.
</P>
<P>
"We will wait. If they don't show up on September 7, we will be
back the next day and wait again. But we want to show our people
that we are ready to talk anytime," Zamora said.
</P>
<P>
He said back-channel negotiations are still being held between
the MILF and the government panel, headed by Edgardo Batenga.
</P>
<P>
According to Zamora, the government is now waiting for the
appropriate response from the MILF.
</P>
<P>
In a separate interview, Batenga said he is now waiting for the
MILF central leadership to inform him on when it is ready to
resume the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"Let me emphasize that the government panel will pursue the
peace process. We'll explore all possible means to bring back MILF
to the negotiating table," Batenga said.
</P>
<P>
He said there is no concrete formula at this time for the
resumption of talks as the government is willing to be flexible on
the matter.
</P>
<P>
Batenga also cited information reaching his office that the
members of the MILF central leadership are meeting to decide on
the date when to resume the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the MILF withdrew all authority to its peace panel to
negotiate a peace agreement with the Philippine government,
following a series of clashes in Mindanao resulting in the falling
of most of MILF's camps in the island.
</P>
<P>
The 15,000-strong MILF is the Philippines' largest rebel group
which has been fighting for an independent Muslim state in
Mindanao for more than two decades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
