<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Reviews Quality Control Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya government is
reviewing the National Standard Act to rally more powers to
control sub-standard goods, the Daily Nation newspaper reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Philip Okundi, managing director of the Kenya Bureau of
Standards (KBS), was quoted as saying that there are some
weaknesses in the present National Standard Act which need to be
removed to deal with those who flout the rules.
</P>
<P>
"The Kenya Bureau of Standards aims at providing quality
services and establishing a more effective quality surveillance of
products coming into the country," he said while launching a
quality testing laboratory at the bureau's Mombassa Office in
southeastern Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the laboratory is part of the wider
strategy of the KBS to make testing services available for all
types of imported or locally-made products, including food,
chemicals, petroleum, electrical and electronic accessories and
building materials, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the laboratory will target sub-standard goods such as
dairy products, juices and water, which pose a health hazard to
the general population.
</P>
<P>
According to Okundi, the Mombassa port is Kenya's largest entry
point for many imported products, some needing immediate testing
in order to accept or bar their entry into the market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
