<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swaziland to Host Convicts in Rwanda Genocide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Swaziland has become the
third country agreeing to have persons convicted by the
International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) to serve their
sentences in the country, newspapers here reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
An agreement to that effect was signed in Mbabane, Swaziland
last Wednesday by the country's Minister for Foreign Affairs and
Trade Albert Shabangu and U. N. Assistant Secretary General and
Registrar of ICTR, Agwu Okali.
</P>
<P>
Okali paid tribute to Swaziland's political stability,
effective institutions and respect for human rights.
</P>
<P>
These factors, he said, in addition to the high standards of
Swaziland's correctional facilities, mean that the tribunal would
have no hesitation to approach the government for this kind of
assistance.
</P>
<P>
Mali and Benin are the other two countries which have reached
agreement with the United Nations to ensure the enforcement of
such sentences.
</P>
<P>
According to the statute of the U.N. tribunal, those convicted
of genocide can serve their sentences in Rwanda or any other state
that has indicated its willingness to U.N. Security Council to
assist the tribunal in this way.
</P>
<P>
Based in Tanzania's northern town of Arusha, ICTR has handed
down only five verdicts since it was set up six years ago to try
leading architects and perpetrators involved in the 1994 genocide
in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Forty-four suspects are currently held in custody in Tanzania
while Rwanda's jam-packed prisons have some 125,000 suspects,
awaiting trial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
