<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin, Mori Remain Apart on Territorial Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Russian President
Vladimir Putin and Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori failed to
narrow their differences over a long-standing territorial dispute
in their first round of talks in Tokyo Monday, dimming prospects
for any breakthrough to conclude a peace treaty between Russia and
Japan by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders, however, agreed to continue talks on the
dispute in their remaining two rounds of discussions during
Putin's three-day official visit which began Sunday, Kyodo News
quoted a Japanese official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Putin and Mori are scheduled to meet again on Monday afternoon,
and then on Tuesday morning for their final session.
</P>
<P>
In the meeting, Putin said that while Russia respects previous
agreements between the two countries, Japan's proposed compromise
on the territorial dispute "is not in full accordance with
Russia's ideas," the official said.
</P>
<P>
Putin also said that Japan's 1998 proposal aimed at resolving
the territorial row cannot be a basis for compromise toward a
peace treaty, Russia's Itar-Tass news agency quoted sources from
the Russian delegation as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese official said Mori called for efforts on both
sides to "seek a mutually acceptable peace treaty," and reiterated
Japan's compromise proposal on the territorial issue.
</P>
<P>
The proposal Japan first made in April 1998 would give Russia
temporary administration over a string of disputed islands as long
as Moscow agrees to draw a demarcation line between the
northernmost of the disputed islands and Russia's Urup Island.
</P>
<P>
The four Russian-held islands off Japan's northernmost
prefecture of Hokkaido, seized by Soviet troops at the end of
World War II, are known as the Northern Territories in Japan and
the Southern Kurils in Russia.
</P>
<P>
Russia rejected Japan's proposal in November 1998. Instead,
Moscow proposed signing an interim "peace, friendship and
cooperation treaty" and leaving the resolution of the islands
problem to a separate pact.
</P>
<P>
The decades-old territorial dispute has prevented Tokyo and
Moscow from concluding a peace treaty although they established
diplomatic ties in 1956.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Russia and Japan agreed to strive toward resolving the
territorial row and concluding the peace treaty by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
As the gap between the two countries on the territorial issue
remains wide, Japanese government officials said Putin and Mori
are likely to effectively give up the year-end target by signing a
document confirming continued treaty talks and calling for a new
guideline to accelerate work by a joint committee dealing with the
territorial row. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
