<HEADLINE> French Truckers Block Oil Storehouses to Protest Rise of Fuel Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 4(Xinhua) -- French truckers began blocking
with trucks oil storehouses and refineries across the country
Monday morning to protest the rise of fuel prices, threatening to
paralyze road circulation.
</P>
<P>
Police and local media reports said that truckers are blocking
oil storehouses in Marseilles, Strasbourg,La Rochelle in the
western coast,Normandy,Massif Central,Lyon, Brittany,and Loire
Atlantique region.
</P>
<P>
The protesting truckers have also blocked the access to the
airport of Nice-Cote d'Azur and are threatening to block an oil
storehouse at the French-Swiss border which provides fuel to the
Swiss airport in Basel.
</P>
<P>
A river port in the central city of Lyon and the accesses to
three refineries near Strasbourg, Lyon and the Normandy port of Le
Havre on the English Channel have also been blocked by the
truckers.
</P>
<P>
Faced with the wave of protests against rise of fuel prices by
fishermen, truckers, taxi drivers and ambulance service, French
Prime Minister Lionel Jospin Sunday promised to take specific
measures to help "the sectors with most difficulties."
</P>
<P>
The oil price has risen to 30 U.S. dollars a barrel, nearly a
50 percent rise in half a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
