<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Ex-Premier Sweeps Beirut Votes in Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's former prime minister
Rafik al-Hariri scored a landslide victory in Sunday's
parliamentary elections, capturing 18 of the 19 seats in capital
Beirut.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Star newspaper reported Monday that initial results in
the southern Lebanon and eastern Bekaa valley districts showed the
Resistance and Development list, anchored by Hezbollah and Amal
militias, headed for victory over several incomplete tickets.
</P>
<P>
Official results of Sunday's polling, the second of two rounds,
were expected to be announced later Monday.
</P>
<P>
Beirut's race culminated that for the first time the capital
elected a woman Ghinwa Jalloul, among Hariri's election list, into
the parliament.
</P>
<P>
There was very little cross-list voting as Hariri has been
imploring supporters to vote for the whole lists as they were.
</P>
<P>
The elections in Beirut were marked by a brisk turnout of Sunni
Muslim voters and poor participation by Christians, Armenians and
Shiite Muslims. Some 40 percent of Beirut's 397,000 eligible voters
cast their votes.
</P>
<P>
Unofficial results underlined loyalty of the Sunni community to
the former prime minister, trouncing incumbent Prime Minister Salim
Hoss and parliament member Tammam Salam, who long dominated the
capital's political scene.
</P>
<P>
Hariri's campaign machine claimed a clean sweep, 18 out of 19
seats in Beirut. He had left a Shiite seat vacant to accommodate
Hezbollah's Mohammed Berjawi.
</P>
<P>
On the national level, he has also secured an overwhelming
majority in parliament through his alliance with Druze leader Walid
Jumblatt, who swept the votes in two of Mount Lebanon's districts
last week, and the support of several other MPs across the country.
</P>
<P>
Despite his known reservations about Hariri, President Emile
Lahoud suggested that MPs would have a decisive say in the choice
of the new premier.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the voting ended at 6 p.m. (1500 GMT) Sunday, Lahoud
released a statement praising the elections as a "model" of
democracy. He referred to the "next big event" of designating a
premier, promising to abide by the "constitution."
</P>
<P>
Sunday's election was relatively trouble-free. There were no
serious problems except that one voter was stabbed and wounded.
</P>
<P>
Under the country's constitution, the current government must
resign when the new parliament first meets on October 17. The
president must then consult MPs over selecting a new premier, with
the results binding for the president. The candidate of the new
premier must get two thirds of the votes in the 128-seat
parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
