<HEADLINE> Arab League Meeting A Test for Unity: UAE Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 4 (Xinhua) -- A leading newspaper in the
United Arab Emirates (UAE) Monday praised the ongoing 114th meeting
of the Arab League foreign ministers council as a test for Arab
unity.
</P>
<P>
The Dubai-based Arabic-language daily Al Bayan commented in an
editorial that the meeting, which opened Sunday in Cairo, is "a
practical test for the required total unity that may prevent the
Arab situation from further collapse."
</P>
<P>
The meeting was reportedly to adopt unanimous stances on
Jerusalem and a comprehensive peace to end the 52-year-old Arab-
Israeli conflict, on the basis of international norms.
</P>
<P>
"The current meeting in Cairo supports Jerusalem's cause and
reaffirms to the world that Arabs have chosen peace as a strategic
choice, not because they are weak, but because they are seeking a
just and comprehensive peace in the Middle East," said the paper.
</P>
<P>
The holy city of Jerusalem is a Palestinian, Arab, Islamic and
Christian city, which constitutes the basic issue in the
Palestinian cause and in the Palestinian-Israeli conflict, it
added.
</P>
<P>
The Cairo meeting or the Jerusalem session reiterated the unity
of Arabs towards Jerusalem as a national right, and affirmed their
refusal to Israel's illegal occupation of the whole city, concluded
the paper.
</P>
<P>
Israel occupied East Jerusalem in the 1967 Mideast War and later
declared the whole of the city as its "eternal and indivisible
capital," a claim the international community has never recognized.
The Arabs are insisting on Palestinian sovereignty over the eastern
sector of Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
