<HEADLINE> Jordan's Private Hospitals Offer Free Treatment to Iraqi Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Ten private hospitals in Jordan
have offered free treatment to Iraqi children in a sign of
solidarity with the sanctions-hit Iraqi people, sources with a pro-
Iraqi committee said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Popular Committee for Solidarity with Iraq said six private
hospitals in Amman and four others outside the capital city have
responded to its call to provide free medical care to Iraqi child
patients who can not get proper treatment in their own country.
</P>
<P>
The committee is a non-profit and independent organization
formed by Jordanian academicians, doctors, lawyers and political
activists, who are eager to see the lifting of the decade-old
international sanctions imposed on Iraq following its 1990 invasion
of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
However, the number of Iraqi child patients to be treated in
Jordan is expected to be highly symbolic as the medical facilities
in the kingdom apparently can not afford to admit Iraqi patients on
a large scale.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian patients resort to public hospitals for free medical
care despite the fact that private hospitals offer better expertise
but at high prices.
</P>
<P>
Iraq said some 1.5 million of its citizens, mostly children and
the elderly, have died of the crippling sanctions due to
malnutrition and a lack of sufficient medical care.
</P>
<P>
The prestigious private Al Hayat Hospital in Amman has offered
full treatment to three Iraqi children a year, and five other
private hospitals offered to treat Iraqi children with brain and
other diseases.
</P>
<P>
Private hospitals in the southern districts of Madaba and Aqaba
have also offered free treatment to Iraqi children with chronic
diseases but on a similarly small scale. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
