<HEADLINE> 10,000 Kenyan Teachers Killed by AIDS Over Five Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 4 (Xinhua) -- At least 10,000 teachers in
Kenya have died of HIV/AIDS over the past five years, a consultant
with the Kenya Institute of Education has said.
</P>
<P>
About 1,400 teachers succumbed to the killer disease last year
alone, Sobbie Mulindi was quoted by Monday's Daily Nation
newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mulindi, also a lecturer at the Nairobi University's Medical
School, said the impact of the disease has adversely affected
staffing and distribution of teachers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
The deaths are expected to lower the quality of education in
the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
He advised the teachers to be sensitized to ways of preventing
the spread of the disease as most people in rural areas look up to
them for information.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Education Ministry has introduced the HIV/AIDS lessons
to primary and secondary schools as well as to teachers' training
colleges.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that almost 1 million Kenyans have died of AIDS
since the first AIDS case was found in the country in 1984.
</P>
</TEXT>
