<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alan Phillips: Oldest Athlete in S. African Olympic Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 4 (Xinhua) -- In 1992 Alan Phillips was
considered too old at the age of 36 to represent South Africa in
badminton at the Barcelona Olympic Games and instead a younger
player, ranked lower than him at that time, was sent.
</P>
<P>
Ironically, after being "too old" eight year ago, Phillips will
become an Olympian at the age of 44 as a pitcher for the South
African baseball team at the Millennium Olympic Games in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Sporting isolation robbed Phillips, the holder of an incredible
27 national badminton titles and a baseball pitcher for 35 years,
of the chance to compete internationally at the highest level.
</P>
<P>
Phillips, now a pither for the Bellville Tigers in Cape Town,
made his South African debut against Chinese Taipei team in 1982,
but had to wait until the end of isolation in the early 1990s to
resume his international career.
</P>
<P>
He said he was dumbfounded when he heard of his selection for
Sydney Games. "To be quite honest I did not think I would make it.
I have been fortunate enough to represent South Africa to go to
the Commonwealth Games in Canada in 1994 and competed in badminton,
but the Olympic Games is something else," Phillips said at the
squad's training camp in Randburg, Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
"It's quite ironic seeing as I had a chance to go to the
Barcelona (Olympic) Games in 1992, but the powers could be decided
otherwise. The real irony is that at the peak of my career
nothing was happening for us in terms of internationl sport, but
in the twilight of my career all the exposure's begun," he joked.
</P>
<P>
His selection for Sydney had an element of good fortune, but
the Olympics can be no better swansong for a man who has been a
fantastic servant to South African sport.
</P>
<P>
"My role in the team is on the pitching side and in a squad of
24. I am looking forward to contributing to the team at the Games,
as I feel you need a bit of experience," Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
"However, it's one thing throwing in South Africa in front of
500 people, but it's another thing playing in international
matches in terms of composure and concentration, and you need some
old hands,"the old athlete added.
</P>
<P>
Phillips is still doing the job for his club Tigers, who won
the league this season in Cape Town with his featuring in over 30
games.
</P>
<P>
He further stressed: "For an older player it's a lot more
demanding to keep up with the young guys and play my part and to
cope with the demands on my time and body. For the past four
months we have been training six days a week, so without the
support of my family it would have been virtually a no-go
situation."
</P>
<P>
"And as our training has gone on, I've dropped a couple of
kilos. Now I feel fitter and stronger than I have in years and
can't wait for the Games," Phillips said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
