<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Achieves Land Acquisition Target of 5 Million Hectares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government has
achieved its land acquisition target of 5 million hectares under
the A1 model scheme and is now preparing tillage units for people
resettled under the fast-track program, The Herald newspaper
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Minister of Lands, Agriculture and Rural
Resettlement Joseph Made as saying on Sunday that at least 1,952
farms have so far been gazetted for compulsory acquisition, and
with more farms expected to be acquired this week, the total
hectarage would come up to about 7 million, way above the targeted
5 million hectares.
</P>
<P>
He said the government would then move onto the A2 and A3
models on which people would be resettled on small-scale and large-
scale farming areas, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Tillage units would be set up across the country to provide
tillage services to people being moved onto the land, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have identified the land that we want to acquire. The base
is set and we should now move into the production channel. What we
now need to look at are all the aspects of tillage -- tractors and
fuel, among other things," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, "95 percent of the major exercise to
identify land for compulsory acquisition is complete and this will
bring peace in the minds of the people."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Minister of Local government, Public Works and
National Housing Ignatius Chombo, who chairs the inter-ministerial
task force on land acquisition, was quoted as saying on Sunday
that a sub-committee on tillage, led by Minister of Rural
Resources and Water Development Joyce Mujuru, will work out the
distribution of tractors per province and the amount of resources
needed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
