<HEADLINE> Wildlife May Feint for Entertainment: Scientists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINHUANGDAO, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Some wild herbivores may
enjoy playing with people by "feinting", according to a group of
experts with the Qinhuangdao Safari Park in north China's Hebei
Province, 300 km from Beijing.
</P>
<P>
This safari park, the largest one of its kind in China,
recorded the behavior of an "aggressive" male giraffe: it would
approach the visitors voluntarily and kick them lightly with his
foreleg just for fun.
</P>
<P>
"It also chases the dragonflies and little springboks," said
the raiser Zheng Xiaohong, "But it doesn't really hurt them."
</P>
<P>
Records also showed that a female zebra "enjoys" feinting
people -- it often runs toward people, "bites" them first and then
turns around and "kicks" them.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang Shouzhong, a zoologist of the park, gnus are
among the most "feint-prone" wild herbivores.
</P>
<P>
"Sometimes a herd of gnus would rush offensively toward people
from one hundred meters away. If the targets keep still calmly,
the gnus would soon retreat. But if the people drew back, they
would keep running around the horrified people without hurting
them," he said.
</P>
<P>
He argues that these animals are doing this just for
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
Wang's colleague Zhang Xueli pointed out that in most cases,
the wild herbivores would not attack people unless they are
disturbed when eating.
</P>
<P>
"However, some animals may also play with people by feinting
especially when they meet small groups of visitors," said Zhang, "
But they are not malicious."
</P>
<P>
Qinhuangdao Safari Park covers an area of 300 hectares, with
some 6,000 wild animals living there.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Coffin to Be Opened in Late September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- A coffin in an ancient tomb
dating back to some 2,000 years is expected to be opened in
Beijing by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists who have been excavating the tomb for eight
months will take the coffin out of the outer caskets and open it
in the Beijing Research Institute of Cultural Heritage in late
September, said Wang Wuyu, vice-director of the institute.
</P>
<P>
The tomb, located 10 kilometers west from downtown Beijing, is
well preserved by a wooden structure, known as "ticou" in Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Ticou is a wooden tomb structure used during the Han dynasties
(206 B.C. to 220 A.D.). The wooden structure encased the tomb and
prevented moisture and earth entering the tomb.
</P>
<P>
This structure was reserved only for the tombs of emperors,
empresses and princes. Thus, archaeologists believed that the
ancient tomb was an imperial mausoleum, though the identification
of the occupant is still unknown.
</P>
<P>
China Central Television (CCTV) telecast live the excavation of
the tomb on August 20. Part of the wooden outer casket was shown,
drawing dozens of millions of Chinese audience.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists expect silk, seals, and other small ornaments to
be found in the coffin, which would help identify the occupant of
the coffin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daily Air Quality Report for 42 Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Five Chinese cities, namely
Shijiazhuang, Taiyuan, Nanjing, Changsha and Guiyang, reported
slight air pollution today, with the highest pollution reading at
118 in Taiyuan.
</P>
<P>
According to the daily air quality report released by the China
Environmental Monitoring Center, level two, or fairly good air
quality, was recorded in other 25 cities.
</P>
<P>
These cities are Beijing, Tianjin, Hohhot, Shenyang, Dalian,
Changchun, Harbin, Shanghai, Suzhou, Nantong, Hangzhou, Wenzhou,
Hefei, Nanchang, Jinan, Yantai, Zhengzhou, Wuhan, Guangzhou,
Chongqing, Chengdu, Kunming, Xi'an, Yinchuan and Urumqi.
</P>
<P>
Particulates less than 10 microns in size were the major
pollutants in most of these cities, except Chongqing and Guiyang,
where sulfur dioxide was the major air pollutant.
</P>
<P>
Twelve cities -- Fuzhou, Xiamen, Qingdao, Shenzhen, Zhuhai,
Shantou, Zhanjiang, Nanning, Haikou, Lhasa, Lanzhou and Xining --
reported excellent air.
</P>
<P>
The center classifies air quality in China's urban areas into
five levels: level one or excellent (pollution reading: not
exceeding 50), level two or fairly good (pollution reading: 51 to
100), level three or slightly polluted (pollution reading: 101 to
200), level four or poor (pollution reading: 201 to 300), and
level five or hazardous (pollution reading: over 301).
</P>
<P>
The 42 cities monitored by the center include the four
municipalities of Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai and Chongqing,
provincial capitals and major cities in the economically developed
coastal areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolia's Foreign Trade Rises in First Seven Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Mongolia's foreign trade
amounted to 543.8 million U.S. dollars in the first seven months
of this year, jumping 32.4 percent compared with the same period
last year, the Mongolian National Statistical Office said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The office said that the total foreign trade balance turned a
deficit of 59.2 million dollars, 9.5 million dollars more than a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
Exports stood at 242.3 million dollars and imports 301.5
million dollars, up 41.7 percent and 25.8 percent respectively
from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the National Statistical Office, exports of
textile rose by 35.2 million dollars, followed by mineral products,
32.1 million dollars, raw and processed hides with 16.4 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
But exports of wood and wooden products declined by 4.4 million
dollars against the same period of 1999.  
</P>
</TEXT>
