<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prestige Chosen Over Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Although many Chinese colleges
promised substantial monetary prizes for the best performing
students in this year's national college entrance exams, most of
these students still chose Qinghua University and Beijing
University, the most prestigious universities in China.
</P>
<P>
Beijing University of Science and Engineering, Harbin
Polytechnic University and other universities in Shanghai and
Guangzhou promised 50,000 yuan (6,204 US dollars) to attract the
top students.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the money offered by the above universities, the
4,000 yuan (482 US dollars) fellowship offered by Beijing
University is very small, as is the prize offered by China's
another top university, Qinghua University.
</P>
<P>
But because of their academic reputation, these two
universities still attracted most of top students from all around
the country, according to a report by the Beijing Morning Daily.
</P>
<P>
Beijing University enrolled 43 of the top students in the
entrance exams from 23 provinces, municipalities and autonomous
regions, while the Qinghua University recruited 70 percent of the
top ten students for the above areas.
</P>
<P>
Educational departments oppose the practice of offering
monetary prizes to attract top students, says the paper.
</P>
<P>
Chinese universities usually start their new semesters in early
September.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
