<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, September 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates' General Secretariat of
Municipalities (GSM) is consulting the latest European Union white
paper on food safety to modify the UAE food safety specifications.
</P>
<P>
The white paper will be used as a base reference to boost the
emirates' own safety specifications, reported the official news
agency WAM on Sunday. (UAE-EU-Food Regulation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HARARE -- An acute shortage of fuel persists in Zimbabwe
despite the government assurances that the problem will end soon.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe has been facing shortages of petrol, diesel and
paraffin since November last year, largely due to the shortage of
foreign currency. A survey by the Zimbabwe News Agency on Sunday
showed the most service stations in Harare, the country's capital,
were dry. (Zimbabwe-Fuel-Crisis)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- The current sugar shortage in Kenya is artificial
and the government would crack down on unscrupulous traders who
hoard the commodity thereby worsening the crisis, the Kenya Sugar
Authority (KSA) has said.
</P>
<P>
The People daily Sunday quoted KSA chief executive Francis
Chahonyo as saying that the government will withdraw licenses from
such traders and confiscate their hidden stocks for release into
the market. (Kenya-Sugar Shortage)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Jordanian Minister of Transport Mohammad Kalaldeh,
Minister of Trade and Industry Wasif Azar will arrive here on
Monday for closer trade ties between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian officials are expected to hold talks with their
Iraqi counterparts and other senior officials on ways of boosting
bilateral economic cooperation and trade exchanges, the official
Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported. (Iraq-Jordan-Ties) 
</P>
