<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Narrow South-North Gap in New Millennium (Part I)  By Yang Qiuyan, Wang Zhenhua </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The agenda of the forthcoming
U.N. summit will highlight, among other topics, the seemingly ever-
enlarging gap between the South and the North.
</P>
<P>
The gap has been a wide concern across the world when the
human being is entering the new Millennium and hoping for a
common prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, during their three-day summit in New York, the more
than 160 top leaders from countries the world over will have to
address themselves to a new world economic order and a hopeful
ensuing solution to the South-North gap.
</P>
<P>
In the past hundred years, the recent 10 years in particular,
the world economic growth has gathered momentum prompted by the
progress of high technology in spite of countless difficulties and
setbacks.
</P>
<P>
While the Western economy, particularly the U.S. economy,
continues to grow, many developing countries have experienced
economic slowdown with some even suffering from economic
stagnation or retrogression.
</P>
<P>
As the result, the gap between the south and the north has
widened. Although the international community has tried to tackle
the problem, the gap between the most developed nations and the
most undeveloped nations is growing.
</P>
<P>
Former International Monetary Fund chief Michel Camdessus
warned that if the South-North gap continues to grow, poverty will
lead to social unrest and conflict which will eventually destroy
the order of the human society.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the current per capita GDP (gross domestic
product) in developed countries is over 60 times of that in
developing countries, compared to 43 times in 1983.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Development Program Human Development Report for 1999
showed 20 percent of the world's population living in developed
countries takes up 86 percent of the world's GDP and 82 percent of
the world market, while more than 75 percent of the world's
population living in developing countries shares only 14 percent
of the world's GDP and 18 percent of the world market.
</P>
<P>
Amid the global economic development, the number of the least
developed nations has risen to 48 today, compared to 36 ten years
ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Narrow South-North Gap in New Millennium (Part III) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At the turn of the century, the international community has
acknowledged more and more clearly that the most important factor
to narrow the South-North disparity is to introduce a just and
reasonable international economic order, which fully reflects and
guarantees the economic interests of developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The developed countries enjoy dominating benefits from the
economic globalization while many developing countries are
burdened with heavy debts mainly due to long-time colonial rule
and plunder, and an international economic order which is unjust
and unreasonable.
</P>
<P>
Many developing countries said cutting and alleviating the
debts of the poorest countries by developed countries can never be
regarded as a kind of charity but their unshirkable responsibility
and obligation.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries have repeatedly called on the rich
countries to stick to their commitment and provide more assistance
to the developing countries. At the same time, in relieving the
debt burdens of the developing countries, the developed countries
should not put unreasonable conditions under the pretext of
improving human rights and democracy, they said.
</P>
<P>
They also called on the developed countries to open markets to
the developing countries, expand trade and transfer new and
advanced technologies to the developing states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Narrow South-North Gap in New Millennium (Part II) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
History shows that besides the interior problems in some
developing countries, the most important cause for the ever
growing gap lies in the failure to establish a just and rational
economic order, which benefits the common development of all
countries.
</P>
<P>
The current world economic order was created and defined by a
few developed countries after World War II, mainly reflecting
their interests. It did not embody the legitimate interests and
reasonable demands of the developing countries, most of which were
still under the colonial or semi-colonial rule at that time.
</P>
<P>
Taking advantage of such an economic order, the developed
states have built up their economic superiority by expanding all
over the world to seek more resources and markets.
</P>
<P>
However, the development of the developing nations were
shackled by the unfair and irrational economic order. Heavily
dependent on resources export, some of the developing countries
met a series of problems such as fund shortage, heavy indebtedness
and worsening conditions in trade and ecological environment. In
some sense, historians said, the developed countries achieved
their economic growth at the expense the interests of developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
Beginning from the 1970s, pressed by many developing countries,
the U.N. stipulated that the rich states provide development
assistance to poor, especially the least developed nations. The
developed states promised that each of them would set aside 0.7
percent of its gross national production (GNP) as official
development assistance.
</P>
<P>
Regrettably, statistics show that most of the developed
countries have failed to honor their commitment, as their
assistance fund has never reached the promised amount and gone
down year by year.
</P>
<P>
The member states of the Organization of Economic Cooperation
and Development (OECD) just provided 0.24 percent of their GNP as
official development assistance in recent years with their per
capita assistance declining from 32 U.S. dollars in 1990 to 19
dollars at present. The United States, the richest country in the
world, just appropriated 0.11 percent of its gross domestic
production (GDP) as official development assistance in the fiscal
year of 2001, setting the lowest record of the post-war period.
</P>
<P>
When providing assistance, the Western nations often attach
some harsh conditions which do not tally with the actual situation
of the poor countries, making the assistance nominal or
inefficient.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Inflation Rate Rises on High Fuel Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's inflation rate is
increasing as higher crude oil prices pushed up retail prices of
gasoline and diesel and increased electricity costs and food
prices, a report from the government said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The consumer price index, the broadest gauge of inflation, rose
O.6 percent in August from the previous month, the biggest monthly
increase since April 1998, it said.
</P>
<P>
On a year-on-year basis, the index rose 2.2 percent, according
to the report.
</P>
<P>
An 80-percent rise in world crude oil prices this year has also
pushed up transportation and production costs in the country, it
said.
</P>
<P>
Inflation may rise further if oil prices extend their gains, it
said, noting that at least 50 consumer-goods makers are now
awaiting governmental approval to raise prices.
</P>
<P>
The government will try to limit price increases to a maximum
of 2.2 percent for the full year through price controls and
informal requests to vendors, the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
