<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seven Drowned in Cambodia as Flooding Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Six children and one
elderly person were drowned in Takeo Province over the weekend as
flood waters continued to rise around the region, according to the
local media Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Takeo Province is the hardest hit," Peou Sarmy, secretary-
general of the Cambodian National Committee for Disaster
Management, was quoted as saying by The Cambodia Daily. "The water
keeps rising."
</P>
<P>
In Takeo, in the south of Cambodia, 9,000 hectares of rice
crops have been destroyed and 252 families have been evacuated to
higher ground. Also in Stung Treng, located in the northeast part
of the nation, 250 hectares of rice crops have been destroyed by
flooding.
</P>
<P>
The local media reported that elsewhere in the country,
unusually heavy monsoon rains threaten more damage to crops and
homes.
</P>
<P>
Authorities will send 4,000 liters of gasoline to Stung Treng,
Kratie and Kompong Cham provinces to prepare for an evacuation of
the area, Peou Sarmy said.
</P>
<P>
In Phnom Penh, about 40,000 sandbags were filled to prevent
flood waters from inundating the capital, Municipal Cabinet Chief
Mann Chhoeun said Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
