<HEADLINE> Myanmar Investigates Foreigners' Visit to Opposition Headquarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar government is
investigating a matter said to be in connection with some 14
foreigners and a team from the U.S. Congress who recently visited
the headquarters here of the opposition political party, the
National League for Democracy (NLD).
</P>
<P>
An official Information Sheet available here Monday morning
charged that certain quarters of the NLD have been conspiring with
the God's Army, an outlawed armed youth organization based on the
Thai-Myanmar border which is said to have been involved in the
smuggling of five remote-controlled bombs into the country to
engage in terrorist activity.
</P>
<P>
NLD senior leaders have been told to remain at home, the
information sheet said, denying that they are put under house
arrest.
</P>
<P>
The government released this information sheet one day after
NLD General Secretary Aung San Suu Kyi and more than a dozen
others were brought back by the authorities before dawn last
Saturday from Dala, the area where they had been barred from
travelling further after staying there for eight days.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, on the same day following the return of the NLD
leaders, the NLD headquarters in the capital's Bahan township was
surrounded by armed police and a search operation was carried out
at the headquarters, eyewitnesses said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
