<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Evaluate State of Emergency in Maluku </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government will
evaluate the implementation of the civilian emergency in Maluku
Province in the eastern part of the country, The Indonesian
Observer reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Amir Hamzah, chairman of the Christian working
group, as saying President Abdurrahman Wahid has ordered
Coordinating Minister for Political, Social and Security Affairs
Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono and Minister for Home Affairs and
Regional Autonomy Soerjadi Soedirdja to evaluate the state of
emergency in the province.
</P>
<P>
Hamzah disclosed details of the request following a meeting
with the president here over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Hamzah said the situation in the province is now more conducive.
</P>
<P>
"If there are attacks, they are due to miscommunication," he
said, adding that the working group has asked the president to
make every effort to halt any further conflict in the region.
</P>
<P>
Hamzah said that after receiving the Christian working group,
the president is due to receive leaders of the Muslim working
group. He will later bring the two groups together in hopes of
reaching agreement on the long-standing conflict.
</P>
<P>
Hamzah added that the president agreed the Maluku communal
conflicts would be settled by the people in Maluku and without
international intervention.
</P>
<P>
The government imposed a state of emergency in Maluku and North
Maluku provinces, where more than 3,500 have died since the bloody
violence between Muslims and Christians erupted in January last
year.
</P>
<P>
Based on Presidential Decree No. 88/2000, the state of
emergency was in force from June 27 to the end of August.
</P>
<P>
There are calls for an extension to the emergency status and an
evaluation of the emergency to determine whether it would be
extended.
</P>
<P>
Maluku Governor Saleh Latuconsina who heads the emergency
authorities supported calls for the central government to extend
the status.
</P>
<P>
"I believe a civil emergency status is still needed,"
Latuconsina was quoted by the paper as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
