<HEADLINE> Indonesian Govt Warns GAM Not to Violate Aceh Cease-fire Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
warned that it would suspend the newly extended humanitarian pause
in Aceh if the separatist Free Aceh Movement (GAM) violates the
accord during the one-month probation period.
</P>
<P>
The warning was made by Foreign Minister Alwi Shihab on Sunday,
The Jakarta Post daily reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the government will evaluate the monitoring
team's monthly report to see if GAM adheres to the ground rules of
the accord which was reached by the two sides last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Friday's accord said the two sides "reconfirmed their support
for the humanitarian pause in Aceh and have agreed in principle to
extend it to the second phase."
</P>
<P>
The first cease-fire accord was signed in May and expired last
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, GAM's commander in Aceh Besar Abutazurra welcomed
the extension of the humanitarian pause and hoped it would pave
the way for a clear political solution to the Aceh issue.
</P>
<P>
But it is unclear whether GAM negotiators are willing to enter
discussion on any other alternatives to separation from Indonesia,
which has been the main call to arms of the separatist group.
</P>
<P>
Alwi said, "We should start to see what we can agree on for the
status of Aceh. For Jakarta, Aceh is an integral part of Indonesia.
We are open to suggestions and we are going to offer special
autonomy for them."
</P>
<P>
But, he stressed, the Indonesian government will not tolerate
any talk about the status of the province outside the context of a
unitary state of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Rebels in Aceh have been fighting for 25 years for independence,
a greater share of oil profits and the right to impose Islamic
religious laws. Thousands have been killed in decades of fighting
between Indonesian security forces and Aceh rebels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
