<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Small Towns to Ease Rural Strain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese experts said that
construction of small towns below the county level is a major way
to ease the tension between the rural population and arable land.
</P>
<P>
According to today's China Daily, with a per capita average of
arable land of about 0.1 hectare, China is expected to have 1.6
billion population in 2030. Nearly 80 percent of the population
are now living in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Du Yin, of the Ministry of Agriculture, said that one key
solution to the strain of land resources is to move rural
population to small towns, where tertiary industry and township
enterprises could be greatly expanded.
</P>
<P>
Already 138 million rural residents do not work in agricultural
production, according China Daily.
</P>
<P>
However, the construction of rural towns should not result in a
flurry of modern towns, said Wen Tiejun, a senior researcher with
the Rural Economic Research Center under the Ministry of
Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Wen said that the ultimate goal of building small towns is to
step up the shuffle of the rural population to small towns bellow
the county level.
</P>
<P>
Du Yin noted that this lies in line with the country's efforts
to pursue sustainable agricultural development and increase the
income of the farmers.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that as more and more rural surplus labors are
taken up by the accelerating process of urbanization, the tension
between arable land and agricultural population will be greatly
eased and the production and quality of farm produce will be
further lifted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
