<HEADLINE> Overseas Firms Welcomed to Bid Chinese Website </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investors will have
access to China's Internet sector in the near future, China Daily
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The organizers of a websites-selling gala promised that foreign
investors will be able to bid on an equal footing with domestic
buyers, the daily said, adding that the items on sale ranging from
domain names, Internet technologies, web content to whole dotcom
companies.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 200 Internet companies will attend the auction
which is scheduled to be held in Beijing at the end of September
by the China International Trade Promotion Committee, a body
affiliated to the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Around 10 websites have submitted their applications for sale
each day and 20 have already have expressed their intention to buy
since registration for the auction began a week ago, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
A number of foreign-funded ventures have also expressed their
intention to attend the bidding.
</P>
<P>
The overall policy climate is relaxed towards foreign
acquisition of and mergers with Chinese dotcoms despite that China
has set some rules on ISPs (Internet service providers), such as a
49 percent cap for foreign stakes in ISP companies, the paper
quoted experts as saying.
</P>
<P>
The paper predicted with confidence that the sector will be
further open to foreigners after China's entry of the World Trade
Organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
