<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, September 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat said here Sunday that
the Palestinian side did not ask the impossible from Israel but
only the proper implementation of all signed agreements between
the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Arafat made the remark in response to the urge of Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak that the Palestinians should show flexibility
in the peace talks. Arafat was speaking after his return form the
Egyptian capital of Cairo, where he took part in the Arab League
foreign ministers' meeting. (Arafat-Signed Agreements)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- U.S. special Middle East peace envoy Dennis Ross
returned to Washington Saturday night after winding up his two-
week mediation between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The main purpose of the visit was to study the grounds for
another Camp David summit and persuade both Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat to soften their
positions on key issues such as Jerusalem so that they could reach
a peace accord on the Israeli-Palestinian final status soon.(
Israel-Ross-Mediation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HARARE -- An acute shortage of fuel persists in Zimbabwe
despite the government assurances that the problem will end soon.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe has been facing shortages of petrol, diesel and
paraffin since November last year, largely due to the shortage of
foreign currency. A survey by the Zimbabwe News Agency on Sunday
showed the most service stations in Harare, the country's capital,
were dry. (Zimbabwe-Fuel-Crisis)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Omani Minister of State for Foreign Affairs Yousef Bin
Alawi Bin Abdullah said Sunday that Arabs have chosen "just and
comprehensive" peace with Israel as a strategic option.
</P>
<P>
In his address to the inaugural session of the Arab League
Foreign Ministers Council, Bin Alawi stressed that such a peace
should lead to the establishment of an independent Palestinian
state with Jerusalem as its capital. (Arab League-Oman-Mideast
Peace)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Over two-thirds of Britons reject the entry of
Europe's single currency, the euro, according to an opinion poll
published Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The poll, carried out by independent pollsters ICM for the
Business for Sterling and the New Europe campaigns, showed 69
percent of Britons remain opposed to euro membership, with only 23
percent in favor and 8 percent saying they did not know.(Euro-
Opposition)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ATHENS -- Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis Sunday called for
the continuation of the U.N.-sponsored proximity talks between
Cyprus' two communities.
</P>
<P>
"We should insist in negotiating, and to get up and leave would
be the worst service we can provide," Simitis said while
addressing this year's International Trade Fair in the northern
Greek city of Thessaloniki. (Greece-Cyprus)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
