<HEADLINE> Zambian Opposition Party Says Zambia Should be Better Managed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Leader of the recently founded
Republic Party, former Environment Minister Ben Mwila said here
Monday that Zambia should be better managed and its resources used
more prudently to foster higher and sustainable growth rates.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference that the policies of free market
economy of the ruling Movement for Multi-Party Democracy (MMD)
were and are good for the nation and failings have been in the
implementation and the misfocus which has now set in.
</P>
<P>
He said Zambia was the second largest economy at its
independence in 1964 in the southern African sub-continent with
its GDP roughly about 35 percent that of South Africa but now its
GDP is only two to three percent that of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Zambia still has large tracts of arable land and much of Zambia
is in the reliable reainbelt, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zambia has one of the vastest water reservoirs both surface and
underground and a refocus can result in a stronger economy which
would furnish his country with means to tackle poverty, said Mwila.
</P>
<P>
Mwila said he believes in government which pays attention to
management and doesn't leave things to chance, a government which
is action-oriented instead of meaningless gimmicks and ceremony.
</P>
<P>
He said that "it is not the so-called crippling external debt
that chokes economic development, but the way we use the available
resources."
</P>
<P>
Zambia with reasonable rates of growth can easily manage annual
debt repayments of 200-300 million U.S. dollars, said Mwila.
</P>
<P>
Mwila lost his ministerial portfolio early last month and days
after he was expelled from MMD on charge of involvement in anti-
party activities.
</P>
<P>
Mwila announced his candidature for the MMD presidency on 26 of
last May in a bid to run for the country's presidency in the
general elections to be held 2001.
</P>
<P>
Mwila launched his Republic Party on August 19.  
</P>
</TEXT>
