<HEADLINE> British Cabinet Office Minister to Quit Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Britain's former Northern
Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam is to stand down as a member of the
parliament at the next general election, the BBC reported on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mowlam, who now serves as the cabinet office minister, said it
was a personal decision and her commitment to Labor was as strong
as ever.
</P>
<P>
She insisted her decision to retire is "nothing to do with
politics," and rejected suggestions of a conspiracy against her.
</P>
<P>
Ms Mowlam was made Northern Ireland Secretary by Prime
Minister Tony Blair in 1997 and steered the 1998 Good Friday
Agreement through its difficult initial stages. But she was
replaced in October 1999 by Peter Mandelson when the peace process
stalled.
</P>
<P>
She had a 15-minute meeting with the prime minister at Number
10 earlier on Monday. Downing Street said she would keep her job
as Cabinet Office minister until the next election.
</P>
<P>
A Downing Street spokesman said Blair believed she would be "a
great loss to the government and a great loss to parliament."
</P>
<P>
Ms Mowlam has consistently been one of the most popular
ministers in Blair's government since New Labor swept to power in
May 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
