<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Proposes a Military Staff College for U.N. Peacekeeping Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Britain on Monday called for
the United Nations to create a military inspectorate and staff
college to command and train U.N. peacekeeping operations around
the world.
</P>
<P>
According to a report released by Foreign Secretary Robin Cook
and Menzies Campbell, the foreign affairs spokesman for the
Liberal Democrats, a smaller party on British political platform,
the college could be located in Britain.
</P>
<P>
The report said the United Nations must provide better-trained
and better-equipped peacekeepers who can respond quickly to
aggression.
</P>
<P>
"No longer must U.N. 'blue helmets' stand by while the most
serious crimes against humanity are being committed," the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The report urged the United Nations to restructure its
peacekeeping role to focus more on conflicts within countries
rather than between nations, and to allow intervention in the
countries where the likelihood of mass murder exists.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the BBC, Cook and Campbell called on the United
Nations to establish a military staff college to train
peacekeepers and a central command center to offer stronger
leadership.
</P>
<P>
"Britain would be a very logical place to have it because of
our expertise in peacekeeping and our commitment to the United
Nations," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
This joint report was released shortly ahead of the U.N.'s
Millennium Summit in New York. About 150 world leaders are
scheduled to meet in the summit and to discuss the United Nations'
peacekeeping missions.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the U.N.'s peacekeeping role has repeatedly
come under fire after the U.N.'s passive performance in some of
the peacekeeping missions failed to achieve the goal.
</P>
<P>
In May, about 500 U.N. peacekeepers were seized by rebels in
the west African nation of Sierra Leone, causing another
embarrassment to the international organization.
</P>
<P>
The British report also suggested that the United Nations
should require member states to provide quarterly assessments of
the soldiers available for peacekeeping operations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000904.0275 </DOCNO>
