<HEADLINE> Schroeder Seeks Far Right Party Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"The federal government will deploy all of its forces to defend
the state and secure the democracy," said Schroeder. "We should
not tolerate anti-Semitism and neo-Nazi violence here in Germany."
</P>
<P>
"Otherwise, Germany's reputation in the world will be hurt and
foreign investors will be scared off," he said.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder told 197 German ambassadors at a foreign policy
meeting that he was determined to put forward the legal steps
aimed to prohibit the far right National Democratic Party (NPD).
</P>
<P>
The government will launch the lawsuit as soon as it has
collected enough testimony against the extremist party, and the
petition "should at least have a little chance at the Federal
Constitutional Court," said Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
A public debate is going on around whether to ban the NPD,
which has been advocating "Germany belongs to Germans" and
encouraging violence against foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Germany's Basic Law says the Constitutional Court is empowered
to outlaw any political party if the party has been ruled as a
threat to democracy.
</P>
<P>
The law has been invoked only twice since 1945, and many are
afraid that the government's petition against the NPD may be ruled
by the Constitutional Court as short of testimony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
