<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Current Account Deficit Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Czech current account
deficit doubled on a year-on-year basis in the first half of this
year, the Czech central bank said Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest statistics, the Czech balance of
payments deficit for the first six months jumped to 27.2 billion
crowns (about 716 million U.S. dollars) from 11.5 billion crowns (
303 million dollars) in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The Czech central bank attributed the growth in the current
account deficit to the rise of the foreign trade deficit. The
trade gap rose to 43.4 billion crowns (about 1.14 billion dollars)
in the January-June period of this year from 25.2 billion crowns (
about 660 million dollars) in the mentioned period last year.
</P>
<P>
Economic analysts said the rise was expected and should have
little impact on full year estimates. But some analysts warned
that if the deficit continued to worsen, the crown would fall.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund expected last month that the
current account deficit of the country would rise to 3.5 percent
of GDP in 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
