<HEADLINE> Greek-Turkish Trade Increases Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- With the recent improvement of
the strained bilateral relations, the trade between Greece and
Turkey has risen sharply this year.
</P>
<P>
The volume of trade between the two neighboring countries has
increased by 38.9 percent to 491.6 million U.S. dollars in the
first half of this year and is expected to reach a record of 1
billion dollars for the year as a whole, the commercial attache
Erdogan Hurbas of the Turkish embassy in Athens said in the
northern Greek city of Thessaloniki Monday.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, Greece's exports to Turkey amounted to 334.4 million
dollars while Turkey's exports to Greece totaled 364.4 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish official also said that Turkish construction
companies have shown strong interest in the projects planned for
the Athens 2004 Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has already given licenses to 11 Greek firms to invest
or expand existing interests in the sectors of commerce, tourism,
merchant marine, processing of farm products, textiles and
chemical products, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, for the first time, is now participating in the 65th
annual Thessaloniki International Trade Fair with its presence
made up of some 75 businesses mounting displays over an area of 1,
500 square meters.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey, both NATO members, have gone to war three
times in the past 26 years over their territorial disputes in the
eastern Aegean Sea and the Cyprus problem, but the two long-time
rivals have since last June taken steps to better their strained
relations by the holding of several rounds of low-level talks and
the signing of a number of bilateral cooperation agreements.
</P>
</TEXT>
