<HEADLINE> Bush, Gore Disagree on Debates Schedule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Republican
presidential candidate George W. Bush and his Democratic rival Al
Gore still disagree on the schedule of debates that will affect
the fall presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Texas Governor Bush has offered three presidential debates,
including one next week, but his proposal was immediately rejected
by Gore.
</P>
<P>
Bush suggested to have the first debate next week on September
12 during a special prime-time edition of NBC's "Meet the Press."
</P>
<P>
He also offered to hold a debate on October 3 in Los Angeles on
CNN's "Larry King Live" and another one on October 17 at
Washington University in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a rally before a Labor Day parade in Chicago suburb
Monday, Bush described Gore's rejection of his proposal as "
Washington doublespeak."
</P>
<P>
"My opponent said he would debate me anyplace, anytime,
anywhere," Bush said. "I said fine. Why don't we just show up...
and discuss our differences."
</P>
<P>
"All of a sudden the words 'anytime, anywhere' don't mean
anything," he added.
</P>
<P>
Gore, however, insisted that Bush must first accept the three
90-minute debates proposed by the Commission on Presidential
Debates.
</P>
<P>
"This is not about what is best for George W. Bush or what is
best for Al Gore. It's about what's best for the American people,"
said Gore, who has accepted the commission's offers for three 90-
minute debates.
</P>
<P>
Gore maintains that the three events proposed by the commission
will reach the widest audience, but Bush's proposed debates will
not.
</P>
<P>
Gore's campaign chairman, William Daley, also said: "We reject
George Bush's plan to shortchange Americans by cutting tens of
millions of people out of the presidential debate audience."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
