<HEADLINE> Britain Calls in Myanmar Ambassador to Protest Crackdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Office minister
John Battle on Monday called in the Myanmar ambassador to protest
at the regime's latest repression of the opposition party, the
Burmese National League for Democracy (NLD).
</P>
<P>
The move was taken after Nobel Prize winner Aung San Suu Kyi
had been kept locked in her residence in Yangon, the capital of
Myanmar, where she was forcibly returned in the early hours of
Saturday following a nine-day standoff in her car after
authorities barred her and her supporters from traveling outside
the capital.
</P>
<P>
"I shall be making clear to Ambassador Hyaw Win that the
forcible return of Aung San Suu Kyi, the de facto house arrest of
NLD leaders and the search of the party headquarters are still
serious infringements of the Burmese (Myanmar) people's human and
political rights," Battle said in a statement issued in London by
the foreign office.
</P>
<P>
"I deplore this treatment of the leader of a democratically
elected party and other members of the NLD," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I shall be conveying to Dr Kyaw Win our protest at the
manhandling of the British ambassador in Rangoon (Yangon) over the
weekend as he tried to establish contact with members of the NLD.
I will also demand that diplomatic access to Aung San Suu Kyi and
her colleagues be immediately restored," the statement quoted
battle as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Office statement said NLD won the 1990 elections in
Burma with an overwhelming 80 percent of the seats, but they have
never been permitted to take office.
</P>
<P>
Britain had persuaded its European Union partners to strengthen
the common EU position on Myanmar, cosponsored resolutions in the
UN Commission on Human Rights and the United Nations General
Assembly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
