<HEADLINE> British Foreign Secretary Meets Former Fijian PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook and Foreign Office Minister John Battle Monday met former
Fiji Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry here in London and called on
Fiji's interim government to restore democratic institutions.
</P>
<P>
Following the meeting, Battle said he had assured Chaudhry,
former ethnic Indian prime minister of the Pacific island state
who was deposed by armed rebels in May and held hostage in Fiji's
parliament building, that Britain was "committed to ensuring that
Fiji rejoins the international community as a constitutional
democracy as soon as possible."
</P>
<P>
"Britain will continue to make clear to the Fiji interim
government that we want to see them map out, and stick to, a
timetable for an early return to democracy, one that is within the
framework of the 1997 constitution and respects the rights of all
the people of Fiji," said Battle.
</P>
<P>
He added that Commonwealth countries will discuss Fiji when
their foreign ministers meet in New York next week, on the
sidelines of a United Nations meeting.
</P>
<P>
Fiji businessman George Speight, who is behind the coup attempt,
wanted the constitution of the Pacific island state redrawn to
exclude ethnic Indians from government.
</P>
<P>
Chaudhry is touring foreign capitals to muster support for the
reinstatement of his ousted government. He has already visited
India, New Zealand and Australia and held talks with European
Union representatives in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
He visited London last week and held talks with Commonwealth
Secretary General Don McKinnon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
