<HEADLINE> Schroeder, Fischer Expect EU to Accept Eastern Members in 2005 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, September 4 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder and Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer Monday said the
European Union would accept first new members in central and
eastern Europe in year 2005 or earlier.
</P>
<P>
At a foreign policy meeting in Berlin, the two rejected the
proposal of Guenter Verheugen, a German Commissar in the European
Commission, to hold a referendum before the EU's eastward
enlargement. Attending the meeting were 197 German ambassadors in
foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder said the EU should be ready to accept new members in
year 2003, and then it should be left for the candidate countries
to decide themselves when they would take the membership.
</P>
<P>
He said, "The eastern candidates should not think that Germany
put its national economical interest above the EU enlargement
policy, we are not willing to see any problem with the time plan."
</P>
<P>
While the EU is under pressure from some member countries to
postpone its time plan for eastward enlargement, Verheugen, a
supporter of eastward enlargement himself, last Saturday indicated
Germany should at first hold a referendum on whether the EU should
accept new members.
</P>
<P>
Verheugen's proposal has aroused anxieties of the candidate
countries such as Poland, the Czech Republic, and Cyprus. But both
Schroeder and Fischer rejected it as "not allowed under Germany's
Basic Law."
</P>
<P>
Fischer said it was "totally unacceptable" as Verheugen had
proposed to modify German's law for a referendum on eastward
enlargement, and he urged the bloc to accelerate the steps.
</P>
<P>
He told the diplomats, "I hope the first group new members of
EU, including Poland, should join the bloc in year 2005 latest."
</P>
<P>
Fischer indicated the leaders of the present 15 EU member
countries should hammer out a "driving map" at the end of this
year to lay down most important steps.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder and Fischer also repeated their support to a "multi-
speed Europe." There should be "deferent integration processes" in
a much-enlarged group, they said.
</P>
<P>
"In a union with 25 or more member countries, not always all
the partners have the same willingness and ability to cooperate,"
said Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
He also supported a reform of EU's decision making process,
stressing the present "one ballot veto" voting system would not
fit an enlarged group.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder said he would call on another EU "reform summit" in
year 2004 aimed to create a "European Charter" that would divide
the power between the Union and member countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
