<HEADLINE> Belarus Rejects NATO's Enlargement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Belarusian government
reiterated on Monday its rebuff to the enlargement of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), considering this "making the
political situation in Europe more tense."
</P>
<P>
President of Belarus Alexander Lukashenko, who will conclude
his visit to Cuba on Tuesday, said at a press conference at this
capital that his country keeps a firm opposition to the
enlargement of the military organization.
</P>
<P>
President Lukashenko was the first leader of the former Soviet
republics to make a call against the NATO's advance towards the
East.
</P>
<P>
He said the NATO "is in the gates of our borders" when asked
what is the purpose of enlarging a military block, and that
nowadays in Europe there are no other military alliances.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the recent entry of the Czech Republic and the
possible future entry of Slovakia to NATO, Lukashenko said that
the situation is going to become more tense for neighboring
countries, and that they will have to strengthen their defense.
</P>
<P>
Lukashenko, invited by Cuban President Fidel Castro, arrived to
this island last Saturday, in the first visit of a Belarusian
leader to Latin America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
